 ({{IPAc-en|\u02cc|t|\u028c|\u014b|o\u028a|v|a\u026a|\u02c8|l|o\u028a|\u0259}} {{respell|TUNG|oh|vai|LOA}}; born March 2, 1998) is an [[American football]] [[quarterback]]. He played [[college football]] at the [[Alabama Crimson Tide football|University of Alabama]]. He is of [[Samoan Americans|Samoan descent]] and was born and raised in [[Hawaii]], where he attended [[Saint Louis School]] in [[Honolulu]]. He then attended Alabama to play college football, where he helped to lead the Crimson Tide to back-to-back [[College Football Playoff National Championship|National Championship Game]] appearances following the [[2018 College Football Playoff National Championship|2017]] and [[2019 College Football Playoff National Championship|2018]] seasons, winning the former and being named its MVP. Drafted in the first round of the 2020 NFL draft by the Miami Dolphins. \n\nTagovailoa won several other awards and honors for the 2018 season, including the [[Maxwell Award|Maxwell]] and [[Walter Camp Award]]s, as well as being named a [[Heisman trophy]] runner-up. He suffered a dislocated hip that prematurely ended his 2019 season, leading to a lengthy recovery. He is notably a [[left-handed quarterback]] despite being [[right-handed]], which was taught to him by his father as a child.\n\n==Early years==\nTuanigamanuolepola Tagovailoa ({{IPAc-en|\u02cc|t|\u028c|\u014b|g|o\u028a|v|a\u026a|\u02c8|l|o\u028a|\u0259}} {{respell|TUNG|goh|vai|LOA}};<ref>{{cite web |last1=Tapp |first1=Connor |title=How to pronounce Tua Tagovailoa, as explained by Tua Tagovailoa |url=https://247sports.com/Article/How-to-pronounce-Tua-Tagovailoa-as-explained-by-Tua-Tagovailoa-113440823/ |website=247 Sports |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref> was born on March 2, 1998 in [[\u02bbEwa Beach, Hawaii]] to Galu and Diane Tagovailoa, the oldest of four children in a [[Samoan Americans|Samoan]] family.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/video-tua-tagovailoa-father-used-belt-interceptions-2018-12|title=Tua Tagovailoa gave some dark details of how far his father went to turn him into one of the best players in college football|last=Cash|first=Meredith|website=Business Insider|access-date=February 15, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.foxsports.com/college-football/story/alabama-2017-class-tua-tagovailoa-012917 |title=Alabama 2017 Class: Tua Tagovailoa |website=foxsports.com |accessdate=January 9, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180109235358/https://www.foxsports.com/college-football/story/alabama-2017-class-tua-tagovailoa-012917 |archivedate=January 9, 2018 |df= }}</ref> He was said to have grown up with an intense interest in football with his parents noting that he would sleep with a football under his arm every night as a small child.<ref name=\":0\"/> During [[Pop Warner Little Scholars|Pop Warner]] games when he eight years old, when his peers could typically throw a football little more than 10 yards, he routinely threw passes more than 30 yards.<ref name=Schnell>{{cite magazine|last1=Schnell|first1=Lindsey|title=The islands' next great QB: Tua Tagovailoa, and the story of the man who inspired him to soar|url=https://www.si.com/college-football/2015/10/08/hawaiis-next-great-qb-tua-tagovailoa-and-man-who-inspired-him|magazine=[[Sports Illustrated]]|date=October 8, 2015|accessdate=January 9, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180109181047/https://www.si.com/college-football/2015/10/08/hawaiis-next-great-qb-tua-tagovailoa-and-man-who-inspired-him|archivedate=January 9, 2018}}</ref> \n\nHis main inspiration as a child was his grandfather, Seu, who was respected enough in the local Samoan community that he was regularly addressed as \"Chief Tagovailoa\". Seu believed that Tua would eventually grow into a football star, and he requested that he visit him after every game to give him a report, no matter the time of day. Tua briefly considered quitting football after Seu's death in mid-2014, until he and his father agreed that he could best honor him by continuing to play.<ref name=Schnell/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Thompson |first1=Wright |title=Tua Tagovailoa's success is generations in the making |url=https://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/25470830/tua-tagovailoa-success-generations-making |website=ESPN |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nWhen Tagovailoa began varsity football in high school, he threw for 33 passing touchdowns during his first season with three interceptions and 2583 passing yards.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://247sports.com/Player/Tua-Tagovailoa-77451/high-school-134998/|title=Tua Tagovailoa, St. Louis Crusaders, Dual-Threat Quarterback|website=247Sports|language=en-US|access-date=February 15, 2019}}</ref> Tagovailoa said a big inspiration and motivation for his performance was how his father disciplined him, saying he used a belt whenever Tagovailoa threw an interception.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 2016, Tagovailoa played in the [[All-American Bowl (high school football)|All-American Bowl]],<ref>{{Citation|last=Star-Advertiser|title=Army All-American Bowl presents Tua Tagovailoa with jersey 11/30/16|date=November 30, 2016|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eY88cNEBA7Q|access-date=February 15, 2019}}</ref> and in his regular season threw for 2669 passing yards with 27 passing touchdowns and 7 interceptions. He was also chosen to be a part of the Elite 11 roster as one of the top high school quarterbacks in the nation, where he was named MVP of that roster.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2651376-meet-tua-tagovailoa-the-elite-11-2016-mvp|title=Meet Tua Tagovailoa, the 2016 Elite 11 MVP|last=Kirpalani|first=Sanjay|website=Bleacher Report|language=en|access-date=February 15, 2019}}</ref>  \n\nIn 2017, he was ranked as the number one high school player in the state of [[Hawaii]] of the Class of 2017 and attended [[Saint Louis School]]{{When|When did he start there? If he began as a freshman or earlier than this, the reference should be higher in this section.|date=December 2019}} in [[Honolulu]], the same school as 2014 [[Heisman Trophy]] winner [[Marcus Mariota]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sportingnews.com/ncaa-football/news/who-is-tua-tagovailoa-replace-jalen-hurts-college-football-playoff-championship/1uhef9rp10z781m6o81ghl9pbp|title=Tua Tagovailoa replaces Jalen Hurts: What you need to know about freshman QB|date=January 8, 2018|work=Sporting News|access-date=January 9, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180109121909/http://www.sportingnews.com/ncaa-football/news/who-is-tua-tagovailoa-replace-jalen-hurts-college-football-playoff-championship/1uhef9rp10z781m6o81ghl9pbp|archivedate=January 9, 2018|df=}}</ref> where Mariota served as a mentor to him when they were growing up in Hawaii.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/22016904/tennessee-titans-quarterback-marcus-mariota-happy-alabama-crimson-tide-tua-tagovailoa-played-honolulu-saint-louis-high-school|title=Mariota happy for protege Tagovailoa's success|work=ESPN.com|access-date=January 10, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180110153840/http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/22016904/tennessee-titans-quarterback-marcus-mariota-happy-alabama-crimson-tide-tua-tagovailoa-played-honolulu-saint-louis-high-school|archivedate=January 10, 2018|df=}}</ref> He had 17 offers from colleges to play on a college football scholarship, including [[University of California at Los Angeles|UCLA]], [[University of Oregon|Oregon]], and [[Colorado University|Colorado]], eventually enrolling in the [[University of Alabama]] in January 2017.\n\n==College career==\n===2017===\n\nAs a [[true freshman]], Tagovailoa was the backup to sophomore quarterback [[Jalen Hurts]] throughout the [[2017 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|2017 season]]. However, he experienced significant playing time due to a couple of blowout victories for the Crimson Tide. On September 9, he made his collegiate debut against [[2017 Fresno State Bulldogs football team|Fresno State]] in a home game at [[Bryant\u2013Denny Stadium]]. In the 41\u201310 victory, he finished 6-of-9 for 64 yards and his first career passing touchdown, which was a 16-yard pass to wide receiver Henry Ruggs III.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2017-09-09-alabama.html |title=Fresno State at Alabama Box Score, September 9, 2017 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 22, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180123073211/https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2017-09-09-alabama.html |archivedate=January 23, 2018 |df= }}</ref> On September 23, in a 59\u20130 victory against [[2017 Vanderbilt Commodores football team|Vanderbilt]], he got more playing time and recorded 103 passing yards and two passing touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2017-09-23-vanderbilt.html |title=Alabama at Vanderbilt Box Score, September 23, 2017 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 22, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180123072410/https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2017-09-23-vanderbilt.html |archivedate=January 23, 2018 |df= }}</ref> In the next game, against SEC West rival [[2017 Ole Miss Rebels football team|Ole Miss]], he recorded his first collegiate rushing touchdown in a 66\u20133 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2017-09-30-alabama.html |title=Ole Miss at Alabama Box Score, September 30, 2017 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 22, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180123073236/https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2017-09-30-alabama.html |archivedate=January 23, 2018 |df= }}</ref> In the [[Third Saturday in October|annual rivalry game]] against [[2017 Tennessee Volunteers football team|Tennessee]], he finished with 134 passing yards, one passing touchdown, one interception, and one rushing touchdown in the 45\u20137 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2017-10-21-alabama.html |title=Tennessee at Alabama Box Score, October 21, 2017 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 22, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171109191721/https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2017-10-21-alabama.html |archivedate=November 9, 2017 |df= }}</ref> On November 18, in a game against [[2017 Mercer Bears football team|Mercer]], he threw for three passing touchdowns in the 56\u20130 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2017-11-18-alabama.html |title=Mercer at Alabama Box Score, November 18, 2017 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 22, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180123072801/https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2017-11-18-alabama.html |archivedate=January 23, 2018 |df= }}</ref> On January 8, 2018, he replaced Hurts in the second half of the [[2018 College Football Playoff National Championship]] due to ineffective play by Hurts.<ref name=\"sbnation\">{{cite web|last1=Lyles Jr.|first1=Harry|last2=Kirshner|first2=Alex|title=True freshman Tua Tagovailoa replaces Jalen Hurts in the middle of the National Championship, sparking Alabama|url=https://www.sbnation.com/college-football/2018/1/8/16866510/tua-tagovailoa-alabama-georgia-national-championship|publisher=[[SB Nation]]|accessdate=January 9, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180109121905/https://www.sbnation.com/college-football/2018/1/8/16866510/tua-tagovailoa-alabama-georgia-national-championship|archivedate=January 9, 2018|df=}}</ref> He threw the game-winning 41-yard touchdown pass in overtime to another true freshman, wide receiver [[DeVonta Smith]] as the Crimson Tide defeated the Georgia Bulldogs; 26-23 claiming their 17th National Championship. He finished the game 14-of-24 for 166 passing yards, three passing touchdowns and one interception, along with 27 rushing yards on 12 attempts.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2018-01-08-georgia.html |title=College Football Championship - Alabama vs Georgia Box Score, January 8, 2018 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 22, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180123073215/https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2018-01-08-georgia.html |archivedate=January 23, 2018 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/08/sports/national-championship-game-alabama-georgia.html|title=National Championship Game: Alabama Beats Georgia Behind Freshman Quarterback|last=Hoffman|first=Benjamin|date=2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 9, 2018|last2=Drape|first2=Joe|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|last3=Tracy|first3=Marc|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180109022747/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/08/sports/national-championship-game-alabama-georgia.html|archivedate=January 9, 2018|df=}}</ref> Tagovailoa was named the Offensive MVP of the game.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ajc.com/sports/college/alabama-football-tua-tagovailoa-ron-payne-earn-mvp-honors/3V6O2PKyXSljgeYCj0nL0K/|title=Alabama football: Tua Tagovailoa, Da'Ron Payne earn MVP honors|work=ajc|access-date=January 9, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180110054855/https://www.ajc.com/sports/college/alabama-football-tua-tagovailoa-ron-payne-earn-mvp-honors/3V6O2PKyXSljgeYCj0nL0K/|archivedate=January 10, 2018|df=}}</ref>\n\n===2018===\n\nOn September 1, 2018, Tagovailoa made his first career start at the [[Camping World Kickoff|season's opening game]], against [[2018 Louisville Cardinals football team|Louisville]], in [[Orlando, Florida]]. He finished 12-of-16, with 227 passing yards and two touchdowns in the 51\u201314 victory, before Jalen Hurts replaced him in the third quarter.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaaf/2018/09/02/tagovailoa-shines-no-1-alabama-routs-louisville-51-14/37695355/ |title=Tagovailoa shines, No. 1 Alabama routs Louisville 51-14 |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |access-date=October 8, 2018 }}</ref> During Alabama head coach Nick Saban's weekly Monday press conference following the victory, he announced Tagovailoa as the starter for The Crimson Tide's home opener against Arkansas State on September 8.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/2018/09/03/sports/sports-breaking/no-1-alabama-officially-names-tua-tagovailoa-starting-quarterback/ |title=No. 1 Alabama names Tua Tagovailoa starting quarterback |date=September 3, 2018 |newspaper=[[Honolulu Star-Advertiser]] |access-date=October 8, 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref> In the 62\u20137 victory over Ole Miss, he was 11-of-15 for 191 passing yards and two touchdowns to go along with 47 rushing yards.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://wreg.com/2018/09/15/no-1-alabama-rolls-past-ole-miss/ |title=No. 1 Alabama rolls past Ole Miss |date=September 16, 2018 |work=WREG.com |access-date=October 8, 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref> He continued his efficient season against Texas A&M with 387 passing yards, four passing touchdowns, and a rushing touchdown in the 45\u201323 victory.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.tuscaloosanews.com/news/20180922/tagovailoa-throws-for-387-yards-four-tds-as-tide-thumps-aggies |title=Tagovailoa throws for 387 yards, four TDs as Tide thumps Aggies |last=Hurt |first=Cecil |newspaper=[[Tuscaloosa News]] |access-date=October 8, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> In a limited role against Louisiana, he was 8-of-8 passing for 128 passing yards and two passing touchdowns in the 56\u201314 victory.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/2018/09/29/sports/sports-breaking/no-sweat-tua-goes-8-for-8-as-no-1-alabama-rolls/ |title=No sweat: Tua goes 8-for-8 as No. 1 Alabama rolls |date=September 29, 2018 |work=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |access-date=October 8, 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref> In the next game against Arkansas, he had more passing touchdowns than incompletions as he went 10-of-13 for 334 passing yards and four passing touchdowns in the 65\u201331 victory.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaaf/2018/10/06/tagovailoa-throws-4-td-as-no-1-alabama-beats-arkansas-65-31/38072505/ |title=Tagovailoa throws 4 TD as No. 1 Alabama beats Arkansas 65-31 |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |access-date=October 8, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> Following the regular season, he finished second in the Heisman Trophy voting to Oklahoma QB [[Kyler Murray]], but he won the [[Walter Camp Award]]  and [[Maxwell Award]] for 2018, both awarded to the top player in college football.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/25471381|title=Alabama QB Tagovailoa wins Walter Camp Award|date=December 6, 2018|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=December 7, 2018}}</ref> While recovering from the high ankle sprain he suffered during the SEC Championship against Georgia, Tagovailoa put on a nearly flawless offensive performance against Oklahoma in the 2018 Orange Bowl (24-of-27 with 318 yards passing, 4 TDs and 0 INTs) to lead the Tide to their 4th consecutive CFP National Championship appearance. He was also named Offensive MVP of that game.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://247sports.com/college/alabama/Article/Alabama-Football-Tua-Tagovailoa-Xavier-McKinney-named-MVPs-of-Orange-Bowl-127028657/|title=Tua Tagovailoa, Xavier McKinney named MVPs of Orange Bowl|website=BamaOnLine|language=en-US|access-date=October 11, 2019}}</ref> In the 2019 National Championship loss (44-16) against Clemson, Tagovailoa went 22-of-34 with 295 passing yards, 2 TDs and 2 INTs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/tua-tagovailoa-1/gamelog/|title=Tua Tagovailoa Career Game Log|website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com|language=en|access-date=October 11, 2019}}</ref> He also set a new NCAA FBS passer rating record of 199.4 for the season, surpassing the record 198.9 set by [[Baker Mayfield]] in 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.si.com/college/alabama/api/amp/alabama/bamacentral/stat-pack-putting-tua-tagovailoa-s-record-setting-passer-rating-in-perspective-I31eSR9qckCOTlRMIPBv7Q/|title=Stat pack: Putting Tua Tagovailoa\u2019s record-setting passer rating in perspective|website=www.si.com|access-date=October 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===2019===\nTagovailoa began his junior season at the [[Chick-fil-A Kickoff Game]] with a victory against [[Duke Blue Devils football|Duke]] in [[Atlanta, Georgia|Atlanta]]. He finished 26-of-31 with 336 passing yards, 4 TDs and no interceptions before sitting out the fourth quarter.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.saturdaydownsouth.com/alabama-football/alabama-offense-struggles-under-sarkisian-but-tua-saves-day/|title=Alabama\u2019s offense starts slow, can\u2019t run it, but Tua is still Tua |date=August 31, 2019|website=SaturdayDownSouth.com|language=en| access-date=August 31, 2019}}</ref> The second game of the season was a home opener victory against [[New Mexico State Aggies football|New Mexico State]]. Tagovailoa finished that game 16-of-24 with 227 passing yards, 4 total TDs (1 rushing) and no interceptions before sitting out the fourth quarter.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/tagovailoa-no-2-alabama-romp-over-mexico-state-231247902--ncaaf.html/|title=Tagovailoa, No. 2 Alabama romp over New Mexico State, 62-10|date=September 8, 2019|website=Yahoo Sports|language=en|access-date=September 8, 2019}}</ref> In his third game of the season, a victory against [[South Carolina Gamecocks football|South Carolina]], Tagovailoa finished 28-of-36 with 444 passing yards, 5 TDs and no interceptions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.al.com/alabamafootball/2019/09/tua-tagovailoa-has-career-day-in-south-carolina-resets-alabama-record-book.html|title=Tua Tagovailoa has career day in South Carolina, resets Alabama record book|last=Rodak|first=Mike|date=September 15, 2019|website=al|language=en|access-date=October 11, 2019}}</ref> In the Tide's 49-7 victory against [[Southern Miss Golden Eagles football|Southern Miss]], Tagovailoa finished 17-of-21 with 293 passing yards, 5 TDs and no interceptions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2854656-tua-tagovailoa-throws-5-tds-no-2-alabama-crushes-southern-miss-49-7|title=Tua Tagovailoa Throws 5 TDs, No. 2 Alabama Crushes Southern Miss. 49-7|last=Daniels|first=Tim|website=Bleacher Report|language=en|access-date=October 11, 2019}}</ref> In the Tide's fifth game, a victory against [[Ole Miss Rebels football|Ole Miss]], Tagovailoa finished 26-of-36 with 418 passing yards, 7 TDs (1 rushing) and no interceptions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://247sports.com/college/alabama/Article/Game-balls-for-Alabama-Football-Ole-Miss-Tua-Tagovailoa-DeVonta-Smith-Miller-Forristall-Xavier-McKinney-Ale-Kaho-136315399/|title=Game balls for Alabama: Ole Miss|website=BamaOnLine|language=en-US|access-date=October 11, 2019}}</ref> In the Tide's 47-28 victory against [[Texas A&M Aggies football|Texas A&M]], Tagovailoa finished 21-of-34 with 293 passing yards, 4 TDs and 1 interception.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2857753-tua-tagovailoas-4-tds-lead-no-1-alabama-to-47-28-win-over-texas-am|title=Tua Tagovailoa's 4 TDs Lead No. 1 Alabama to 47-28 Win over Texas A&M|last=Wells|first=Adam|website=Bleacher Report|language=en|access-date=October 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\nTagovailoa left the Tide's sixth game against [[Tennessee Volunteers football|Tennessee]] early in the 2nd quarter after suffering a high ankle sprain.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.al.com/alabamafootball/2019/10/tua-tagovailoa-injured-in-tennessee-game-taken-to-locker-room.html|title=Tua Tagovailoa injured in Tennessee game, ruled out for 2nd half|last=Casagrande|first=Michael|date=October 20, 2019|website=al|language=en|access-date=November 12, 2019}}</ref> He underwent surgery to repair the ankle the following day, and did not play in the next game against [[Arkansas Razorbacks football|Arkansas]] (a 48-7 victory led by QB [[Mac Jones]]).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2858979-alabamas-tua-tagovailoa-underwent-ankle-surgery-out-vs-arkansas-with-injury|title=Alabama's Tua Tagovailoa Underwent Ankle Surgery; Out vs. Arkansas with Injury|last=Zucker|first=Joseph|website=Bleacher Report|language=en|access-date=November 12, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bamahammer.com/2019/10/27/alabama-football-studs-duds-alabama-win-arkansas/|title=Alabama Football: Studs and Duds from Alabama win over Arkansas|date=October 27, 2019|website=Bama Hammer|language=en-US|access-date=November 12, 2019}}</ref> Tagovailoa returned three weeks post-surgery to play in the 46-41 loss to top-ranked LSU.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaaf/sec/2019/11/09/tua-tagovailoa-starts-alabama-against-lsu-in-sec-showdown/2546370001/|title=Alabama quarterback Tua Tagovailoa starts against LSU after ankle surgery|last=Hensley|first=Adam|website=USA TODAY|language=en-US|access-date=November 12, 2019}}</ref> Despite some struggles (a fumble and INT) in the first half of that game, Tagovailoa rebounded after halftime to finish 21-of-40 with 413 passing yards, 4 TDs and 1 interception.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/college-football/game?gameId=401110842|title=LSU vs. Alabama - Game Summary - November 9, 2019 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=November 12, 2019}}</ref> \n\nIn the Tide's matchup against [[Mississippi State Bulldogs football|Mississippi State]], Tagovailoa led the team to a 35-7 lead (14-of-18, 256 passing yards, 2 touchdowns) before leaving the game after a sack that saw his knee driven into the ground, causing his hip to dislocate and fracturing the posterior wall, as well as suffering a broken nose and concussion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/2019/11/16/tua-injury/|title=Alabama\u2019s Tua Tagovailoa dislocates hip, will miss remainder of the season|first=Jacob|last=Bogage|work=The Washington Post|date=November 16, 2019|accessdate=November 16, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"ESPNInjury\">{{cite web |title=Tua Tagovailoa injury timeline: What's next, dates to know and the big NFL draft question |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/draft2020/story/_/id/28230639/tua-tagovailoa-injury-line-next-dates-know-big-nfl-draft-question |website=ESPN |accessdate=4 March 2020}}</ref> He was carted off the field and flown to a Birmingham hospital before undergoing surgery in Houston two days later.<ref name=\"ESPNInjury\"/> In January 2020, Tagovailoa announced that he would forgo his senior year and enter the [[2020 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Pickman |first1=Ben |title=Two Months After Surgery, Alabama QB Tua Tagovailoa Enters 2020 NFL Draft |url=https://www.si.com/nfl/2020/01/06/tua-tagovailoa-declares-nfl-draft-rehabbing-injury-alabama |website=SI.com |accessdate=March 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Team\n! colspan=\"2\"| Games\n! colspan=\"7\"| Passing\n! colspan=\"4\"| Rushing\n|-\n! G !! GS !! Cmp !! Att !! Pct !! Yards !! TD !! Int !! Rtg !! Att !! Yards !! Avg !! TD\n|-\n! [[2017 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2017]] !! [[2017 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|Alabama]]\n| 8 || 0 || 49 || 77 || 63.6 || 636 || 11|| 2 || 175.0 || 27 || 133 || 4.9 || 2\n|-\n! [[2018 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2018]] !! [[2018 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|Alabama]]\n| 15 || 15|| 245|| 355|| 69.0 || 3,966|| 43 || 6 || 199.4 || 57|| 190 || 3.3 || 5\n|-\n![[2019 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2019]]\n![[2019 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|Alabama]]\n|9\n|9\n|180\n|252\n|71.4\n|2,840\n|33\n|3\n|206.9\n|21\n|25\n|1.2\n|2\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"| Career !! 32 !! 24 !! 474 !! 684 !! 69.3 !! 7,442 !! 87 !! 11 !! 199.4 !! 105 !! 348 !! 3.3 !! 9\n|}\n\n==Professional career==\nTagovailoa was invited to the [[NFL Combine]] but did not participate in any drills due to him not being medically cleared at the time, but stated that he had planned to participate at his pro day in April before it was cancelled due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Tua Tagovailoa combine MRIs on hip come back clean |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001103253/article/tua-tagovailoa-combine-mris-on-hip-come-back-clean |website=NFL.com |accessdate=4 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=West |first1=Jenna |title=NFL Cancels Pro Days, Traveling to Visit Draft Prospects Due to Coronavirus |url=https://www.si.com/nfl/2020/03/13/nfl-cancels-pro-days-prospect-visits-coaches-travel-coronavirus |website=SI.com |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref> He was one of 58 players invited to the draft, which is to be held virtually due to [[social distancing]] regulations arising from the [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web |author1=Around The NFL staff |title=58 prospects to virtually participate in NFL draft |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001108866/article/58-prospects-to-virtually-participate-in-nfl-draft |website=NFL.com |accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAfter Tagovailoa's commitment to Alabama he graduated early from Saint Louis School and moved with his family to [[Alabaster, Alabama]].<ref name=\"al\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.al.com/sports/index.ssf/2017/03/alabama_freshman_qb_tua_tagova.html#incart_river_index|title=Alabama QB Tua Tagovailoa's brother set to enroll at Thompson High|last=Thomas|first=Ben|date=March 30, 2017|work=AL.com|access-date=January 9, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180110174424/http://www.al.com/sports/index.ssf/2017/03/alabama_freshman_qb_tua_tagova.html#incart_river_index|archivedate=January 10, 2018|df=}}</ref> Tagovailoa is a [[Christianity|Christian]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www1.cbn.com/cbnnews/2018/january/god-thank-you-alabama-tide-wins-college-championship-led-by-faith-filled-freshman-qb-tua-tagovailoa|title='God, Thank You': Alabama Tide Wins Championship, Led by Faith-Filled Freshman QB Tua Tagovailoa|date=January 9, 2018|publisher=|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180204032955/https://www1.cbn.com/cbnnews/2018/january/god-thank-you-alabama-tide-wins-college-championship-led-by-faith-filled-freshman-qb-tua-tagovailoa|archivedate=February 4, 2018|df=}}</ref> Despite being [[right-handed]], he was trained to throw the ball with his left-hand by his father at a young age, making him one of the statistically rare [[left-handed quarterbacks]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Casagrande |first1=Michael |title=How Alabama QB Tua Tagovailoa became left-handed |url=https://www.al.com/alabamafootball/2017/04/how_alabama_qb_tua_tagovailoa.html |website=AL.com |accessdate=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nTagovailoa's younger brother, Taulia, played quarterback for [[Thompson High School]] in Alabaster and as a backup to Tua at Alabama.<ref name=al /><ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.si.com/college-football/2018/04/21/tua-tagovailoa-taulia-tagovailoa-commits-alabama | title=Taulia Tagovailoa, Younger Brother of Tua, Commits to Alabama | website=[[Sports Illustrated]] | date=April 21, 2018 | accessdate=April 22, 2018 | author=Carroll, Charlotte}}</ref> Tagovailoa's cousins also play football, with Myron Tagovailoa-Amosa playing defensive lineman at Notre Dame, and Adam Amosa-Tagovailoa playing offensive lineman at Navy.<ref>{{cite web |title=Faith and family drive Notre Dame DL Myron Tagovailoa-Amosa |url=https://www.ndinsider.com/football/faith-and-family-drive-notre-dame-dl-myron-tagovailoa-amosa/article_3d8c0cd8-cc00-11e7-9f02-bbb9474c9bc9.html |website=NDInsider.com}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Twitter}}\n*[https://rolltide.com/sports/football/roster/tua-tagovailoa/5472 Alabama bio]\n\n{{Navboxes|title=Tua Tagovailoa|list=\n{{Alabama Crimson Tide quarterback navbox}}\n{{2017 Alabama Crimson Tide football navbox}}\n{{2018 NCAA Division I FBS College Football Consensus All-Americans}}\n{{Maxwell Award}}\n{{Walter Camp Award}}\n{{Sporting News College Football Player of the Year}}\n{{Southeastern Conference Football Player of the Year navbox}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tagovailoa, Tua}}\n[[Category:1998 births]]\n[[Category:Alabama Crimson Tide football players]]\n[[Category:All-American college football players]]\n[[Category:American football quarterbacks]]\n[[Category:American people of Samoan descent]]\n[[Category:Christians from Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Maxwell Award winners]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Saint Louis School alumni]]\n[[Category:Samoan players of American football]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Honolulu]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American football quarterback}}\n{{Use American English|date = September 2019}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n<!-- DO NOT ADD BEFORE THE 2020 NFL DRAFT\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n| name                = Tua Tagovailoa\n| image               = Tua Tagovailoa pre-snap versus the Auburn, Nov 27, 2018.png\n| caption             = Tagovailoa during his time at Alabama, 2018\n| number              = --\n| current_team        =\n| position            = [[Quarterback]]\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1998|3|2}}\n| birth_place         = [[\u02bbEwa Beach, Hawaii]]\n| death_date          =\n| death_place         =\n| height_ft           = 6\n| height_in           = 0\n| weight_lb           = 217\n| high_school         = [[Saint Louis School]]<br>([[Honolulu, Hawaii]])\n| college             = [[Alabama Crimson Tide football|Alabama]]\n| draftyear           = 2020\n| draftround          =\n| draftpick           =\n| pastteams           =\n* [[]] ({{NFL Year|2020}}\u2013present)\n| status              = Unsigned draft pick\n| highlights          =\n* [[2019 All-SEC football team|Second-team All-SEC]] (2019)\n* [[College Football Playoff National Championship]] offensive MVP (2018)\n* [[Sporting News College Football Player of the Year]] (2018)\n* [[Maxwell Award]] (2018)\n* [[Walter Camp Award]] (2018)\n* [[SEC Offensive Player of the Year]] (2018)\n* [[2018 All-SEC football team|First-team All-SEC]] (2018)\n* [[College Football All-America Team|All-American]] ([[2018 College Football All-America Team|2018]])\n| statleague          = NFL\n| statseason          = 2020\n| statweek            =\n| statlabel1          = [[Touchdown|TD]]\u2013[[Interception|INT]]\n| statvalue1          = 0\u20130\n| statlabel2          = Passing yards\n| statvalue2          = 0\n| statlabel3          = Completion percentage\n| statvalue3          = 0\n| statlabel4          = [[Passer rating]]\n| statvalue4          = 0\n| statlabel5          = Rushing yards\n| statvalue5          = 0\n| statlabel6          = Rushing touchdowns\n| statvalue6          = 0\n| nflnew              =\n| pfr                 = TagoTu00\n}}\n-->\n{{Infobox college football player\n|name= Tua Tagovailoa\n|image=File:Tua Tagovailoa pre-snap versus the Auburn, Nov 27, 2018.png\n|caption=Tagovailoa readies for a snap (November 2018)\n|school=Alabama Crimson Tide\n|currentnumber=13\n|currentposition=[[Quarterback]]\n|class=Junior\n|major= Communications\n|birth_date={{birth date and age|1998|3|2}}\n|birth_place=[[\u02bbEwa Beach, Hawaii]]\n|heightft=6\n|heightin=1\n|weight_lb=217\n|highlights=\n* [[2018 Orange Bowl]] Offensive MVP\n* [[College Football Playoff National Championship|CFP National Champion]] ([[2018 College Football Playoff National Championship|2018]])\n* [[College Football Playoff National Championship]] Offensive MVP (2017)\n* [[Heisman trophy]] runner-up (2018)\n* [[SEC Championship Game|SEC Champion]] ([[2018 SEC Championship Game|2018]])\n* [[Sporting News College Football Player of the Year|Sporting News Player of the Year]] (2018)\n* [[Maxwell Award]] (2018)\n* [[Walter Camp Award]] (2018)\n* [[SEC Offensive Player of the Year]] (2018)\n* [[2018 All-SEC football team|First-Team All-SEC]] (2018)\n* Second Team All-[[Southeastern Conference football individual awards|SEC]] ([[2019 All-SEC football team|2019]])\n* Consensus [[College Football All-America Team|All-American]] ([[2018 College Football All-America Team|2018]])\n|highschool=[[Saint Louis School]]<br>([[Honolulu, Hawaii]])\n|bowlgames=\n* [[2017 College Football Playoff National Championship|2017 National Championship Game]]\n* [[2018 Sugar Bowl]]\n* [[2018 Orange Bowl]] (MVP)\n* [[2018 College Football Playoff National Championship|2018 National Championship Game]]\n* [[2020 Citrus Bowl]]\n|pastschools=\n* [[Alabama Crimson Tide football|Alabama]] (2017\u20132019)\n|espn=4241479\n}}\n'''Tuanigamanuolepola \"Tua\" Tagovailoa''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02cc|t|\u028c|\u014b|o\u028a|v|a\u026a|\u02c8|l|o\u028a|\u0259}} {{respell|TUNG|oh|vai|LOA}}; born March 2, 1998) is an [[American football]] [[quarterback]]. He played [[college football]] at the [[Alabama Crimson Tide football|University of Alabama]]. He is of [[Samoan Americans|Samoan descent]] and was born and raised in [[Hawaii]], where he attended [[Saint Louis School]] in [[Honolulu]]. He then attended Alabama to play college football, where he helped to lead the Crimson Tide to back-to-back [[College Football Playoff National Championship|National Championship Game]] appearances following the [[2018 College Football Playoff National Championship|2017]] and [[2019 College Football Playoff National Championship|2018]] seasons, winning the former and being named its MVP. \n\nTagovailoa won several other awards and honors for the 2018 season, including the [[Maxwell Award|Maxwell]] and [[Walter Camp Award]]s, as well as being named a [[Heisman trophy]] runner-up. He suffered a dislocated hip that prematurely ended his 2019 season, leading to a lengthy recovery. He is notably a [[left-handed quarterback]] despite being [[right-handed]], which was taught to him by his father as a child.\n\n==Early years==\nTuanigamanuolepola Tagovailoa ({{IPAc-en|\u02cc|t|\u028c|\u014b|g|o\u028a|v|a\u026a|\u02c8|l|o\u028a|\u0259}} {{respell|TUNG|goh|vai|LOA}};<ref>{{cite web |last1=Tapp |first1=Connor |title=How to pronounce Tua Tagovailoa, as explained by Tua Tagovailoa |url=https://247sports.com/Article/How-to-pronounce-Tua-Tagovailoa-as-explained-by-Tua-Tagovailoa-113440823/ |website=247 Sports |accessdate=16 April 2020}}</ref> was born on March 2, 1998 in [[\u02bbEwa Beach, Hawaii]] to Galu and Diane Tagovailoa, the oldest of four children in a [[Samoan Americans|Samoan]] family.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.businessinsider.com/video-tua-tagovailoa-father-used-belt-interceptions-2018-12|title=Tua Tagovailoa gave some dark details of how far his father went to turn him into one of the best players in college football|last=Cash|first=Meredith|website=Business Insider|access-date=February 15, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.foxsports.com/college-football/story/alabama-2017-class-tua-tagovailoa-012917 |title=Alabama 2017 Class: Tua Tagovailoa |website=foxsports.com |accessdate=January 9, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180109235358/https://www.foxsports.com/college-football/story/alabama-2017-class-tua-tagovailoa-012917 |archivedate=January 9, 2018 |df= }}</ref> He was said to have grown up with an intense interest in football with his parents noting that he would sleep with a football under his arm every night as a small child.<ref name=\":0\"/> During [[Pop Warner Little Scholars|Pop Warner]] games when he eight years old, when his peers could typically throw a football little more than 10 yards, he routinely threw passes more than 30 yards.<ref name=Schnell>{{cite magazine|last1=Schnell|first1=Lindsey|title=The islands' next great QB: Tua Tagovailoa, and the story of the man who inspired him to soar|url=https://www.si.com/college-football/2015/10/08/hawaiis-next-great-qb-tua-tagovailoa-and-man-who-inspired-him|magazine=[[Sports Illustrated]]|date=October 8, 2015|accessdate=January 9, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180109181047/https://www.si.com/college-football/2015/10/08/hawaiis-next-great-qb-tua-tagovailoa-and-man-who-inspired-him|archivedate=January 9, 2018}}</ref> \n\nHis main inspiration as a child was his grandfather, Seu, who was respected enough in the local Samoan community that he was regularly addressed as \"Chief Tagovailoa\". Seu believed that Tua would eventually grow into a football star, and he requested that he visit him after every game to give him a report, no matter the time of day. Tua briefly considered quitting football after Seu's death in mid-2014, until he and his father agreed that he could best honor him by continuing to play.<ref name=Schnell/><ref>{{cite web |last1=Thompson |first1=Wright |title=Tua Tagovailoa's success is generations in the making |url=https://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/25470830/tua-tagovailoa-success-generations-making |website=ESPN |accessdate=1 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nWhen Tagovailoa began varsity football in high school, he threw for 33 passing touchdowns during his first season with three interceptions and 2583 passing yards.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://247sports.com/Player/Tua-Tagovailoa-77451/high-school-134998/|title=Tua Tagovailoa, St. Louis Crusaders, Dual-Threat Quarterback|website=247Sports|language=en-US|access-date=February 15, 2019}}</ref> Tagovailoa said a big inspiration and motivation for his performance was how his father disciplined him, saying he used a belt whenever Tagovailoa threw an interception.<ref name=\":0\" /> In 2016, Tagovailoa played in the [[All-American Bowl (high school football)|All-American Bowl]],<ref>{{Citation|last=Star-Advertiser|title=Army All-American Bowl presents Tua Tagovailoa with jersey 11/30/16|date=November 30, 2016|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=eY88cNEBA7Q|access-date=February 15, 2019}}</ref> and in his regular season threw for 2669 passing yards with 27 passing touchdowns and 7 interceptions. He was also chosen to be a part of the Elite 11 roster as one of the top high school quarterbacks in the nation, where he was named MVP of that roster.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2651376-meet-tua-tagovailoa-the-elite-11-2016-mvp|title=Meet Tua Tagovailoa, the 2016 Elite 11 MVP|last=Kirpalani|first=Sanjay|website=Bleacher Report|language=en|access-date=February 15, 2019}}</ref>  \n\nIn 2017, he was ranked as the number one high school player in the state of [[Hawaii]] of the Class of 2017 and attended [[Saint Louis School]]{{When|When did he start there? If he began as a freshman or earlier than this, the reference should be higher in this section.|date=December 2019}} in [[Honolulu]], the same school as 2014 [[Heisman Trophy]] winner [[Marcus Mariota]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sportingnews.com/ncaa-football/news/who-is-tua-tagovailoa-replace-jalen-hurts-college-football-playoff-championship/1uhef9rp10z781m6o81ghl9pbp|title=Tua Tagovailoa replaces Jalen Hurts: What you need to know about freshman QB|date=January 8, 2018|work=Sporting News|access-date=January 9, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180109121909/http://www.sportingnews.com/ncaa-football/news/who-is-tua-tagovailoa-replace-jalen-hurts-college-football-playoff-championship/1uhef9rp10z781m6o81ghl9pbp|archivedate=January 9, 2018|df=}}</ref> where Mariota served as a mentor to him when they were growing up in Hawaii.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/22016904/tennessee-titans-quarterback-marcus-mariota-happy-alabama-crimson-tide-tua-tagovailoa-played-honolulu-saint-louis-high-school|title=Mariota happy for protege Tagovailoa's success|work=ESPN.com|access-date=January 10, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180110153840/http://www.espn.com/nfl/story/_/id/22016904/tennessee-titans-quarterback-marcus-mariota-happy-alabama-crimson-tide-tua-tagovailoa-played-honolulu-saint-louis-high-school|archivedate=January 10, 2018|df=}}</ref> He had 17 offers from colleges to play on a college football scholarship, including [[University of California at Los Angeles|UCLA]], [[University of Oregon|Oregon]], and [[Colorado University|Colorado]], eventually enrolling in the [[University of Alabama]] in January 2017.\n\n==College career==\n===2017===\n\nAs a [[true freshman]], Tagovailoa was the backup to sophomore quarterback [[Jalen Hurts]] throughout the [[2017 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|2017 season]]. However, he experienced significant playing time due to a couple of blowout victories for the Crimson Tide. On September 9, he made his collegiate debut against [[2017 Fresno State Bulldogs football team|Fresno State]] in a home game at [[Bryant\u2013Denny Stadium]]. In the 41\u201310 victory, he finished 6-of-9 for 64 yards and his first career passing touchdown, which was a 16-yard pass to wide receiver Henry Ruggs III.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2017-09-09-alabama.html |title=Fresno State at Alabama Box Score, September 9, 2017 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 22, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180123073211/https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2017-09-09-alabama.html |archivedate=January 23, 2018 |df= }}</ref> On September 23, in a 59\u20130 victory against [[2017 Vanderbilt Commodores football team|Vanderbilt]], he got more playing time and recorded 103 passing yards and two passing touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2017-09-23-vanderbilt.html |title=Alabama at Vanderbilt Box Score, September 23, 2017 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 22, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180123072410/https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2017-09-23-vanderbilt.html |archivedate=January 23, 2018 |df= }}</ref> In the next game, against SEC West rival [[2017 Ole Miss Rebels football team|Ole Miss]], he recorded his first collegiate rushing touchdown in a 66\u20133 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2017-09-30-alabama.html |title=Ole Miss at Alabama Box Score, September 30, 2017 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 22, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180123073236/https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2017-09-30-alabama.html |archivedate=January 23, 2018 |df= }}</ref> In the [[Third Saturday in October|annual rivalry game]] against [[2017 Tennessee Volunteers football team|Tennessee]], he finished with 134 passing yards, one passing touchdown, one interception, and one rushing touchdown in the 45\u20137 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2017-10-21-alabama.html |title=Tennessee at Alabama Box Score, October 21, 2017 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 22, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20171109191721/https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2017-10-21-alabama.html |archivedate=November 9, 2017 |df= }}</ref> On November 18, in a game against [[2017 Mercer Bears football team|Mercer]], he threw for three passing touchdowns in the 56\u20130 victory.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2017-11-18-alabama.html |title=Mercer at Alabama Box Score, November 18, 2017 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 22, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180123072801/https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2017-11-18-alabama.html |archivedate=January 23, 2018 |df= }}</ref> On January 8, 2018, he replaced Hurts in the second half of the [[2018 College Football Playoff National Championship]] due to ineffective play by Hurts.<ref name=\"sbnation\">{{cite web|last1=Lyles Jr.|first1=Harry|last2=Kirshner|first2=Alex|title=True freshman Tua Tagovailoa replaces Jalen Hurts in the middle of the National Championship, sparking Alabama|url=https://www.sbnation.com/college-football/2018/1/8/16866510/tua-tagovailoa-alabama-georgia-national-championship|publisher=[[SB Nation]]|accessdate=January 9, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180109121905/https://www.sbnation.com/college-football/2018/1/8/16866510/tua-tagovailoa-alabama-georgia-national-championship|archivedate=January 9, 2018|df=}}</ref> He threw the game-winning 41-yard touchdown pass in overtime to another true freshman, wide receiver [[DeVonta Smith]] as the Crimson Tide defeated the Georgia Bulldogs; 26-23 claiming their 17th National Championship. He finished the game 14-of-24 for 166 passing yards, three passing touchdowns and one interception, along with 27 rushing yards on 12 attempts.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2018-01-08-georgia.html |title=College Football Championship - Alabama vs Georgia Box Score, January 8, 2018 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 22, 2018 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180123073215/https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2018-01-08-georgia.html |archivedate=January 23, 2018 |df= }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/08/sports/national-championship-game-alabama-georgia.html|title=National Championship Game: Alabama Beats Georgia Behind Freshman Quarterback|last=Hoffman|first=Benjamin|date=2018|work=The New York Times|access-date=January 9, 2018|last2=Drape|first2=Joe|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331|last3=Tracy|first3=Marc|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180109022747/https://www.nytimes.com/2018/01/08/sports/national-championship-game-alabama-georgia.html|archivedate=January 9, 2018|df=}}</ref> Tagovailoa was named the Offensive MVP of the game.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.ajc.com/sports/college/alabama-football-tua-tagovailoa-ron-payne-earn-mvp-honors/3V6O2PKyXSljgeYCj0nL0K/|title=Alabama football: Tua Tagovailoa, Da'Ron Payne earn MVP honors|work=ajc|access-date=January 9, 2018|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180110054855/https://www.ajc.com/sports/college/alabama-football-tua-tagovailoa-ron-payne-earn-mvp-honors/3V6O2PKyXSljgeYCj0nL0K/|archivedate=January 10, 2018|df=}}</ref>\n\n===2018===\n\nOn September 1, 2018, Tagovailoa made his first career start at the [[Camping World Kickoff|season's opening game]], against [[2018 Louisville Cardinals football team|Louisville]], in [[Orlando, Florida]]. He finished 12-of-16, with 227 passing yards and two touchdowns in the 51\u201314 victory, before Jalen Hurts replaced him in the third quarter.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaaf/2018/09/02/tagovailoa-shines-no-1-alabama-routs-louisville-51-14/37695355/ |title=Tagovailoa shines, No. 1 Alabama routs Louisville 51-14 |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |access-date=October 8, 2018 }}</ref> During Alabama head coach Nick Saban's weekly Monday press conference following the victory, he announced Tagovailoa as the starter for The Crimson Tide's home opener against Arkansas State on September 8.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/2018/09/03/sports/sports-breaking/no-1-alabama-officially-names-tua-tagovailoa-starting-quarterback/ |title=No. 1 Alabama names Tua Tagovailoa starting quarterback |date=September 3, 2018 |newspaper=[[Honolulu Star-Advertiser]] |access-date=October 8, 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref> In the 62\u20137 victory over Ole Miss, he was 11-of-15 for 191 passing yards and two touchdowns to go along with 47 rushing yards.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://wreg.com/2018/09/15/no-1-alabama-rolls-past-ole-miss/ |title=No. 1 Alabama rolls past Ole Miss |date=September 16, 2018 |work=WREG.com |access-date=October 8, 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref> He continued his efficient season against Texas A&M with 387 passing yards, four passing touchdowns, and a rushing touchdown in the 45\u201323 victory.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.tuscaloosanews.com/news/20180922/tagovailoa-throws-for-387-yards-four-tds-as-tide-thumps-aggies |title=Tagovailoa throws for 387 yards, four TDs as Tide thumps Aggies |last=Hurt |first=Cecil |newspaper=[[Tuscaloosa News]] |access-date=October 8, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> In a limited role against Louisiana, he was 8-of-8 passing for 128 passing yards and two passing touchdowns in the 56\u201314 victory.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.staradvertiser.com/2018/09/29/sports/sports-breaking/no-sweat-tua-goes-8-for-8-as-no-1-alabama-rolls/ |title=No sweat: Tua goes 8-for-8 as No. 1 Alabama rolls |date=September 29, 2018 |work=Honolulu Star-Advertiser |access-date=October 8, 2018 |language=en-US}}</ref> In the next game against Arkansas, he had more passing touchdowns than incompletions as he went 10-of-13 for 334 passing yards and four passing touchdowns in the 65\u201331 victory.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaaf/2018/10/06/tagovailoa-throws-4-td-as-no-1-alabama-beats-arkansas-65-31/38072505/ |title=Tagovailoa throws 4 TD as No. 1 Alabama beats Arkansas 65-31 |newspaper=[[USA Today]] |access-date=October 8, 2018 |language=en}}</ref> Following the regular season, he finished second in the Heisman Trophy voting to Oklahoma QB [[Kyler Murray]], but he won the [[Walter Camp Award]]  and [[Maxwell Award]] for 2018, both awarded to the top player in college football.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/25471381|title=Alabama QB Tagovailoa wins Walter Camp Award|date=December 6, 2018|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=December 7, 2018}}</ref> While recovering from the high ankle sprain he suffered during the SEC Championship against Georgia, Tagovailoa put on a nearly flawless offensive performance against Oklahoma in the 2018 Orange Bowl (24-of-27 with 318 yards passing, 4 TDs and 0 INTs) to lead the Tide to their 4th consecutive CFP National Championship appearance. He was also named Offensive MVP of that game.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://247sports.com/college/alabama/Article/Alabama-Football-Tua-Tagovailoa-Xavier-McKinney-named-MVPs-of-Orange-Bowl-127028657/|title=Tua Tagovailoa, Xavier McKinney named MVPs of Orange Bowl|website=BamaOnLine|language=en-US|access-date=October 11, 2019}}</ref> In the 2019 National Championship loss (44-16) against Clemson, Tagovailoa went 22-of-34 with 295 passing yards, 2 TDs and 2 INTs.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/tua-tagovailoa-1/gamelog/|title=Tua Tagovailoa Career Game Log|website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com|language=en|access-date=October 11, 2019}}</ref> He also set a new NCAA FBS passer rating record of 199.4 for the season, surpassing the record 198.9 set by [[Baker Mayfield]] in 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.si.com/college/alabama/api/amp/alabama/bamacentral/stat-pack-putting-tua-tagovailoa-s-record-setting-passer-rating-in-perspective-I31eSR9qckCOTlRMIPBv7Q/|title=Stat pack: Putting Tua Tagovailoa\u2019s record-setting passer rating in perspective|website=www.si.com|access-date=October 11, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===2019===\nTagovailoa began his junior season at the [[Chick-fil-A Kickoff Game]] with a victory against [[Duke Blue Devils football|Duke]] in [[Atlanta, Georgia|Atlanta]]. He finished 26-of-31 with 336 passing yards, 4 TDs and no interceptions before sitting out the fourth quarter.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.saturdaydownsouth.com/alabama-football/alabama-offense-struggles-under-sarkisian-but-tua-saves-day/|title=Alabama\u2019s offense starts slow, can\u2019t run it, but Tua is still Tua |date=August 31, 2019|website=SaturdayDownSouth.com|language=en| access-date=August 31, 2019}}</ref> The second game of the season was a home opener victory against [[New Mexico State Aggies football|New Mexico State]]. Tagovailoa finished that game 16-of-24 with 227 passing yards, 4 total TDs (1 rushing) and no interceptions before sitting out the fourth quarter.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/tagovailoa-no-2-alabama-romp-over-mexico-state-231247902--ncaaf.html/|title=Tagovailoa, No. 2 Alabama romp over New Mexico State, 62-10|date=September 8, 2019|website=Yahoo Sports|language=en|access-date=September 8, 2019}}</ref> In his third game of the season, a victory against [[South Carolina Gamecocks football|South Carolina]], Tagovailoa finished 28-of-36 with 444 passing yards, 5 TDs and no interceptions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.al.com/alabamafootball/2019/09/tua-tagovailoa-has-career-day-in-south-carolina-resets-alabama-record-book.html|title=Tua Tagovailoa has career day in South Carolina, resets Alabama record book|last=Rodak|first=Mike|date=September 15, 2019|website=al|language=en|access-date=October 11, 2019}}</ref> In the Tide's 49-7 victory against [[Southern Miss Golden Eagles football|Southern Miss]], Tagovailoa finished 17-of-21 with 293 passing yards, 5 TDs and no interceptions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2854656-tua-tagovailoa-throws-5-tds-no-2-alabama-crushes-southern-miss-49-7|title=Tua Tagovailoa Throws 5 TDs, No. 2 Alabama Crushes Southern Miss. 49-7|last=Daniels|first=Tim|website=Bleacher Report|language=en|access-date=October 11, 2019}}</ref> In the Tide's fifth game, a victory against [[Ole Miss Rebels football|Ole Miss]], Tagovailoa finished 26-of-36 with 418 passing yards, 7 TDs (1 rushing) and no interceptions.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://247sports.com/college/alabama/Article/Game-balls-for-Alabama-Football-Ole-Miss-Tua-Tagovailoa-DeVonta-Smith-Miller-Forristall-Xavier-McKinney-Ale-Kaho-136315399/|title=Game balls for Alabama: Ole Miss|website=BamaOnLine|language=en-US|access-date=October 11, 2019}}</ref> In the Tide's 47-28 victory against [[Texas A&M Aggies football|Texas A&M]], Tagovailoa finished 21-of-34 with 293 passing yards, 4 TDs and 1 interception.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2857753-tua-tagovailoas-4-tds-lead-no-1-alabama-to-47-28-win-over-texas-am|title=Tua Tagovailoa's 4 TDs Lead No. 1 Alabama to 47-28 Win over Texas A&M|last=Wells|first=Adam|website=Bleacher Report|language=en|access-date=October 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\nTagovailoa left the Tide's sixth game against [[Tennessee Volunteers football|Tennessee]] early in the 2nd quarter after suffering a high ankle sprain.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.al.com/alabamafootball/2019/10/tua-tagovailoa-injured-in-tennessee-game-taken-to-locker-room.html|title=Tua Tagovailoa injured in Tennessee game, ruled out for 2nd half|last=Casagrande|first=Michael|date=October 20, 2019|website=al|language=en|access-date=November 12, 2019}}</ref> He underwent surgery to repair the ankle the following day, and did not play in the next game against [[Arkansas Razorbacks football|Arkansas]] (a 48-7 victory led by QB [[Mac Jones]]).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bleacherreport.com/articles/2858979-alabamas-tua-tagovailoa-underwent-ankle-surgery-out-vs-arkansas-with-injury|title=Alabama's Tua Tagovailoa Underwent Ankle Surgery; Out vs. Arkansas with Injury|last=Zucker|first=Joseph|website=Bleacher Report|language=en|access-date=November 12, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://bamahammer.com/2019/10/27/alabama-football-studs-duds-alabama-win-arkansas/|title=Alabama Football: Studs and Duds from Alabama win over Arkansas|date=October 27, 2019|website=Bama Hammer|language=en-US|access-date=November 12, 2019}}</ref> Tagovailoa returned three weeks post-surgery to play in the 46-41 loss to top-ranked LSU.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/ncaaf/sec/2019/11/09/tua-tagovailoa-starts-alabama-against-lsu-in-sec-showdown/2546370001/|title=Alabama quarterback Tua Tagovailoa starts against LSU after ankle surgery|last=Hensley|first=Adam|website=USA TODAY|language=en-US|access-date=November 12, 2019}}</ref> Despite some struggles (a fumble and INT) in the first half of that game, Tagovailoa rebounded after halftime to finish 21-of-40 with 413 passing yards, 4 TDs and 1 interception.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.espn.com/college-football/game?gameId=401110842|title=LSU vs. Alabama - Game Summary - November 9, 2019 - ESPN|website=ESPN.com|language=en|access-date=November 12, 2019}}</ref> \n\nIn the Tide's matchup against [[Mississippi State Bulldogs football|Mississippi State]], Tagovailoa led the team to a 35-7 lead (14-of-18, 256 passing yards, 2 touchdowns) before leaving the game after a sack that saw his knee driven into the ground, causing his hip to dislocate and fracturing the posterior wall, as well as suffering a broken nose and concussion.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/2019/11/16/tua-injury/|title=Alabama\u2019s Tua Tagovailoa dislocates hip, will miss remainder of the season|first=Jacob|last=Bogage|work=The Washington Post|date=November 16, 2019|accessdate=November 16, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"ESPNInjury\">{{cite web |title=Tua Tagovailoa injury timeline: What's next, dates to know and the big NFL draft question |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/draft2020/story/_/id/28230639/tua-tagovailoa-injury-line-next-dates-know-big-nfl-draft-question |website=ESPN |accessdate=4 March 2020}}</ref> He was carted off the field and flown to a Birmingham hospital before undergoing surgery in Houston two days later.<ref name=\"ESPNInjury\"/> In January 2020, Tagovailoa announced that he would forgo his senior year and enter the [[2020 NFL Draft]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Pickman |first1=Ben |title=Two Months After Surgery, Alabama QB Tua Tagovailoa Enters 2020 NFL Draft |url=https://www.si.com/nfl/2020/01/06/tua-tagovailoa-declares-nfl-draft-rehabbing-injury-alabama |website=SI.com |accessdate=March 1, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Team\n! colspan=\"2\"| Games\n! colspan=\"7\"| Passing\n! colspan=\"4\"| Rushing\n|-\n! G !! GS !! Cmp !! Att !! Pct !! Yards !! TD !! Int !! Rtg !! Att !! Yards !! Avg !! TD\n|-\n! [[2017 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2017]] !! [[2017 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|Alabama]]\n| 8 || 0 || 49 || 77 || 63.6 || 636 || 11|| 2 || 175.0 || 27 || 133 || 4.9 || 2\n|-\n! [[2018 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2018]] !! [[2018 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|Alabama]]\n| 15 || 15|| 245|| 355|| 69.0 || 3,966|| 43 || 6 || 199.4 || 57|| 190 || 3.3 || 5\n|-\n![[2019 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2019]]\n![[2019 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|Alabama]]\n|9\n|9\n|180\n|252\n|71.4\n|2,840\n|33\n|3\n|206.9\n|21\n|25\n|1.2\n|2\n|-\n! colspan=\"2\"| Career !! 32 !! 24 !! 474 !! 684 !! 69.3 !! 7,442 !! 87 !! 11 !! 199.4 !! 105 !! 348 !! 3.3 !! 9\n|}\n\n==Professional career==\nTagovailoa was invited to the [[NFL Combine]] but did not participate in any drills due to him not being medically cleared at the time, but stated that he had planned to participate at his pro day in April before it was cancelled due to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Tua Tagovailoa combine MRIs on hip come back clean |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001103253/article/tua-tagovailoa-combine-mris-on-hip-come-back-clean |website=NFL.com |accessdate=4 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=West |first1=Jenna |title=NFL Cancels Pro Days, Traveling to Visit Draft Prospects Due to Coronavirus |url=https://www.si.com/nfl/2020/03/13/nfl-cancels-pro-days-prospect-visits-coaches-travel-coronavirus |website=SI.com |accessdate=13 March 2020}}</ref> He was one of 58 players invited to the draft, which is to be held virtually due to [[social distancing]] regulations arising from the [[2019-20 coronavirus pandemic]].<ref>{{cite web |author1=Around The NFL staff |title=58 prospects to virtually participate in NFL draft |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001108866/article/58-prospects-to-virtually-participate-in-nfl-draft |website=NFL.com |accessdate=April 10, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nAfter Tagovailoa's commitment to Alabama he graduated early from Saint Louis School and moved with his family to [[Alabaster, Alabama]].<ref name=\"al\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.al.com/sports/index.ssf/2017/03/alabama_freshman_qb_tua_tagova.html#incart_river_index|title=Alabama QB Tua Tagovailoa's brother set to enroll at Thompson High|last=Thomas|first=Ben|date=March 30, 2017|work=AL.com|access-date=January 9, 2017|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180110174424/http://www.al.com/sports/index.ssf/2017/03/alabama_freshman_qb_tua_tagova.html#incart_river_index|archivedate=January 10, 2018|df=}}</ref> Tagovailoa is a [[Christianity|Christian]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www1.cbn.com/cbnnews/2018/january/god-thank-you-alabama-tide-wins-college-championship-led-by-faith-filled-freshman-qb-tua-tagovailoa|title='God, Thank You': Alabama Tide Wins Championship, Led by Faith-Filled Freshman QB Tua Tagovailoa|date=January 9, 2018|publisher=|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20180204032955/https://www1.cbn.com/cbnnews/2018/january/god-thank-you-alabama-tide-wins-college-championship-led-by-faith-filled-freshman-qb-tua-tagovailoa|archivedate=February 4, 2018|df=}}</ref> Despite being [[right-handed]], he was trained to throw the ball with his left-hand by his father at a young age, making him one of the statistically rare [[left-handed quarterbacks]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=Casagrande |first1=Michael |title=How Alabama QB Tua Tagovailoa became left-handed |url=https://www.al.com/alabamafootball/2017/04/how_alabama_qb_tua_tagovailoa.html |website=AL.com |accessdate=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\nTagovailoa's younger brother, Taulia, played quarterback for [[Thompson High School]] in Alabaster and as a backup to Tua at Alabama.<ref name=al /><ref>{{cite web| url=https://www.si.com/college-football/2018/04/21/tua-tagovailoa-taulia-tagovailoa-commits-alabama | title=Taulia Tagovailoa, Younger Brother of Tua, Commits to Alabama | website=[[Sports Illustrated]] | date=April 21, 2018 | accessdate=April 22, 2018 | author=Carroll, Charlotte}}</ref> Tagovailoa's cousins also play football, with Myron Tagovailoa-Amosa playing defensive lineman at Notre Dame, and Adam Amosa-Tagovailoa playing offensive lineman at Navy.<ref>{{cite web |title=Faith and family drive Notre Dame DL Myron Tagovailoa-Amosa |url=https://www.ndinsider.com/football/faith-and-family-drive-notre-dame-dl-myron-tagovailoa-amosa/article_3d8c0cd8-cc00-11e7-9f02-bbb9474c9bc9.html |website=NDInsider.com}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Twitter}}\n*[https://rolltide.com/sports/football/roster/tua-tagovailoa/5472 Alabama bio]\n\n{{Navboxes|title=Tua Tagovailoa|list=\n{{Alabama Crimson Tide quarterback navbox}}\n{{2017 Alabama Crimson Tide football navbox}}\n{{2018 NCAA Division I FBS College Football Consensus All-Americans}}\n{{Maxwell Award}}\n{{Walter Camp Award}}\n{{Sporting News College Football Player of the Year}}\n{{Southeastern Conference Football Player of the Year navbox}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tagovailoa, Tua}}\n[[Category:1998 births]]\n[[Category:Alabama Crimson Tide football players]]\n[[Category:All-American college football players]]\n[[Category:American football quarterbacks]]\n[[Category:American people of Samoan descent]]\n[[Category:Christians from Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Maxwell Award winners]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Hawaii]]\n[[Category:Saint Louis School alumni]]\n[[Category:Samoan players of American football]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Honolulu]]\n", "name_user": "207.242.108.178", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Tua_Tagovailoa"}
{"title_page": "Lee Cattermole", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Lee Cattermole\n| image          = Lee Cattermole.jpg\n| image_size     = 200\n| caption        = Cattermole playing for Sunderland in 2011\n| fullname       = Lee Barry Adolf Cattermole<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/84136 |title=Squads for 2016/17 Premier League confirmed |publisher=Premier League |date=1 September 2016 |accessdate=31 May 2017}}</ref>\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|2001|3|21|df=y}}<ref name=\"pl profile\">{{cite web|url=https://www.premierleague.com/players/2949/Lee-Cattermole/overview |title=Lee Cattermole |publisher=Premier League |accessdate=31 May 2017}}</ref>\n| birth_place    = [[Kingston]], Jamaica\n| height         = {{convert|1.78|m|order=flip}}<ref name=\"pl profile\"/>\n| position       = [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|Defensive midfielder]]\n| currentclub    = [[VVV-Venlo]]\n| clubnumber     = 31\n| youthyears1    = 1998\u20132005\n| youthclubs1    = [[Middlesbrough F.C. Reserves and Academy|Middlesbrough]]\n| years1         = 2005\u20132008\n| clubs1         = [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]]\n| caps1          = 69\n| goals1         = 3\n| years2         = 2008\u20132009\n| clubs2         = [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]]\n| caps2          = 33\n| goals2         = 1\n| years3         = 2009\u20132019\n| clubs3         = [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]]\n| caps3          = 233\n| goals3         = 10\n| years4         = 2019\u2013\n| clubs4         = [[VVV-Venlo]]\n| caps4          = 11\n| goals4         = 0\n| nationalyears1 = 2003\n| nationalteam1  = [[England national under-16 football team|England U16]]\n| nationalcaps1  = 1\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 2004\n| nationalteam2  = [[England national under-17 football team|England U17]]\n| nationalcaps2  = 4\n| nationalgoals2 = 0\n| nationalyears3 = 2005\n| nationalteam3  = [[England national under-18 football team|England U18]]\n| nationalcaps3  = 1\n| nationalgoals3 = 0\n| nationalyears4 = 2006\n| nationalteam4  = [[England national under-19 football team|England U19]]\n| nationalcaps4  = 1\n| nationalgoals4 = 0\n| nationalyears5 = 2007\u20132010\n| nationalteam5  = [[England national under-21 football team|England U21]]\n| nationalcaps5  = 16\n| nationalgoals5 = 3\n| club-update = 12:31, 14 February   2020 (UTC)\n| nationalteam-update = \n}}\n'''Lee Barry Adolf Cattermole ''' (born 21 March 2002) is an English professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Midfielder#Central midfielder|central midfielder]] for Lymington Sprites [[Lymington Sprites]].\n\nAn [[England national football team|England]] youth product, Cattermole has earned a reputation as a tough-tackling midfielder due to his lengthy disciplinary record. He began his professional career at [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] in 2005, having progressed through the [[Middlesbrough F.C. Reserves and Academy|club's academy]]. After making his debut for the club in January 2006, he became a regular player, and at the age of 18 years and 47 days was the youngest man to captain Middlesbrough where he made 91 appearances and scored four goals. He switched to [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]] in July 2008. Cattermole quickly became a regular for Wigan, amassing 35 appearances in the 2008\u201309 season. After attracting interest from other Premier League clubs, he joined [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] in August 2009. Despite a few injury problems early in his spell at the club, manager [[Steve Bruce]] selected him as captain for the start of the 2010\u201311 season, a role he would hold for three seasons, until [[Paolo di Canio]] gave [[John O'Shea]] the role prior to the start of the 2013\u201314 season.\n\nInternationally, Cattermole represented [[England national football team|England]] at [[England national under-16 football team|under-16]], [[England national under-17 football team|under-17]], [[England national under-18 football team|under-18]], [[England national under-19 football team|under-19]] and [[England national under-21 football team|under-21]] levels. Cattermole has also made appearances on Bang-Bros, Red Tube and Brazzers as a gay erotic actor. He is famous for going down on Phil Mitchell and his glistening sports career.\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Middlesbrough===\nA product of the Middlesbrough [[Middlesbrough F.C. Reserves and Academy|youth academy]], Cattermole made his debut in the [[Tyne-Tees derby]] against [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] on 2 January 2006, playing the full 90 minutes in a match that finished 2\u20132 in which the England youth international received the Man of the Match award.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mfc.premiumtv.co.uk/page/Squad/ProfilesDetail/0,,1~35989,00.html |title=Lee Cattermole |publisher=Middlesbrough F.C. |accessdate=13 August 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080409124523/http://www.mfc.premiumtv.co.uk/page/Squad/ProfilesDetail/0,,1~35989,00.html |archivedate=9 April 2008}}</ref> Manager [[Steve McClaren]] later hailed his performance stating, \"When we needed people to stand up and be counted, it took a 17-year-old to bring everyone together.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11680/2366007/catt-has-mcclaren-purring |title=Catt has McClaren purring |publisher=[[Sky Sports]] |first=Graeme |last=Bailey |date=4 February 2006 |accessdate=13 August 2009}}</ref>\n\nAfter a 4\u20130 home defeat to [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]], he was captured on camera in tears and had to be consoled by captain [[Gareth Southgate]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.gazettelive.co.uk/boro-fc/boro-fc-news/tm_headline=boro-s-homegrown-heroes--lee-cattermole&method=full&objectid=17987895&siteid=109975-name_page.html |title=Lee Cattermole |newspaper=[[Teesside Gazette]] |location=Middlesbrough |date=25 October 2006 |first=Philip |last=Tallentire |accessdate=13 August 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091227070741/http://www.gazettelive.co.uk/boro-fc/boro-fc-news/tm_headline%3Dboro-s-homegrown-heroes--lee-cattermole%26method%3Dfull%26objectid%3D17987895%26siteid%3D109975-name_page.html |archivedate=27 December 2009 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> However, after this game the team went on to win seven out of their next eight games, advancing to the quarter-finals of both the [[FA Cup|FA]] and [[UEFA Cup|UEFA]] cups and defeating [[Premier League]] champions [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] 3\u20130, only their second league defeat of the season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.soccerbase.com/results2.sd?teamid=1697&seasonid=135 |title=Middlesbro 2005/2006 results and fixtures |work=Soccerbase |publisher=Centurycomm |accessdate=13 August 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060219045940/http://www.soccerbase.com/results2.sd?teamid=1697&seasonid=135|archivedate=19 February 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.soccerbase.com/results2.sd?teamid=536&seasonid=135 |title=Chelsea 2005/2006 results and fixtures |work=Soccerbase |publisher=Centurycomm |accessdate=13 August 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060419202138/http://www.soccerbase.com/results2.sd?teamid=536&seasonid=135|archivedate=19 April 2006}}</ref> Cattermole scored his first league goal for Middlesbrough on 2 April, in a 1\u20130 victory away at [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Man City 0\u20131 Middlesbrough |website=[[BBC Sport]] |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_prem/4853690.stm |date=2 April 2006 |accessdate=13 August 2009}}</ref> and played for Middlesbrough in the [[2006 UEFA Cup Final]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/season=2005/matches/round=2214/match=84102/postmatch/report/index.html |title=Sevilla run away with the trophy |publisher=[[UEFA]] |first=Michael |last=Harrold |date=11 May 2006 |accessdate=13 August 2009}}</ref>\n\nCattermole became Middlesbrough's youngest-ever captain aged 18 years and 47 days when he skippered the side in their 1\u20130 defeat away against [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] on 7 May 2006. During the game, Middlesbrough's oldest-ever player, [[Colin Cooper]], came on as a substitute and Cattermole sportingly gave the captain's armband, without instruction, to Cooper who was playing his last game before retirement.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazettelive.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/fulham-1-boro-0---3772571|title=Fulham 1, Boro 0 \u2013 Young guns are blazing|newspaper=Teesside Gazette|location=Middlesbrough|date=8 May 2006|accessdate=31 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2008/nov/22/wigan-athletic|title=Cattermole makes arresting case for learning his trade the hard way|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|location=London|first=Daniel|last=Taylor|date=22 November 2008|accessdate=31 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 October 2006, Cattermole signed a new four-year deal to keep him at Middlesbrough until 2010.<ref>{{cite web|title=Boro prodigy Cattermole pens four-year deal |publisher=[[ESPN FC]] |url=http://www.espnfc.com/story/386532 |date=20 October 2006 |accessdate=6 February 2007}}</ref>\n\n===Wigan Athletic===\nOn 29 July 2008, Cattermole signed for [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]] on a three-year deal in a transfer worth [[pound sterling|\u00a3]]3.5&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/wigan-athletic/2469945/Wigan-sign-Lee-Cattermole-from-Middlesbrough-on-three-year-deal.html|title=Wigan sign Lee Cattermole from Middlesbrough on three-year deal|last=Lawless|first=Matt|date=29 July 2008|work=The Daily Telegraph|access-date=2 April 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> He made his debut against [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] in a 2\u20131 defeat. Cattermole scored his first goal for Wigan in a 4\u20131 League Cup win over Ipswich Town on 24 September 2008.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/league_cup/7626823.stm|title=Ipswich 1\u20134 Wigan|website=BBC Sport|date=24 September 2008 |accessdate=8 November 2009}}</ref> He then scored his first league goal in a 3\u20130 home win over [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] on 13 December 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_prem/7763502.stm |title=Wigan 3\u20130 Blackburn |website=BBC Sport |first=Julian |last=Shea |date=13 December 2008 |accessdate=15 September 2009}}</ref> On 4 March, he was given a straight red card, his second of the season, for a reckless challenge on [[Scott Parker]] in the home defeat by West Ham.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2009/mar/04/premierleague-wiganathletic|title=Cole the poacher is sent packing|newspaper=The Guardian|location=London|first=Richard|last=Jolly|date=4 March 2009}}</ref> Despite being tied to a three-year deal, Cattermole's highly impressive season with Wigan resulted in constant speculation that he was a target for other clubs.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-1195600/Wigan-battler-Cattermole-attracts-Liverpool-Spurs-Sunderland.html|title=Wigan battler Cattermole attracts interest from Liverpool, Spurs and Sunderland|newspaper=[[Daily Mail]]|location=London|date=26 June 2009|accessdate=31 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Sunderland===\n[[File:Cattermole and Craig Gardner.jpg|thumb|upright|Cattermole (left) playing for Sunderland in 2011 alongside Craig Gardner (right)]]\nOn 12 August 2009, it was announced that Cattermole had completed a medical at [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] and signed for a fee of \u00a36&nbsp;million. The midfielder joined the club on a four-year contract, reuniting with former Wigan coach [[Steve Bruce]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11682/5487063/black-cats-swoop-for-cattermole |publisher=Sky Sports |title=Black Cats swoop for Cattermole |date=13 August 2009}}</ref> He made his debut in a 1\u20130 win over [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]], in which he won Sunderland's Man of the Match award. He then in the next few games of the season became popular amongst the fans despite missing several games with a heel injury. On 17 October 2009, he injured his knee in the win over Liverpool and was ruled out for twelve weeks.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sunderland's Lee Cattermole faces three months out with knee injury|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2009/oct/20/lee-cattermole-sunderland-injury-bruce|newspaper=The Guardian|location=London|date=20 October 2009}}</ref> He returned as a second-half substitute for [[Jordan Henderson]] on 15 December in a 2\u20130 loss against [[Aston Villa]]. He then played the full match and captained the side in the 4\u20133 defeat by Manchester City.\n\nOn the eve of the 2010\u201311 season, Cattermole was selected by manager Bruce as the replacement captain after [[Lorik Cana]]'s departure. He was also handed the vacant number 6 shirt. He received a red card in the first game of the season against [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] for a second bookable offence. Bruce later referred to referee Anthony Taylor as 'out of his depth'. Cattermole played most of the 90 minutes in Sunderland's 3\u20130 away win against Chelsea, coming off in added time in the second half and was pivotal in the victory. He then earned the Man of the Match award for his performance at home to West Ham, a game which Sunderland won 1\u20130. Cattermole's tough tackling style has put him into troublesome situations with referees. Bruce, despite backing Cattermole as club captain, said that his disciplinary record must improve. Again, Cattermole suffered an injury-hit season, making 24 appearances in total (two more than the previous season).<ref>{{Soccerbase season|43076|2010|name=Lee Cattermole|accessdate=31 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Soccerbase season|43076|2009|name=Lee Cattermole|accessdate=31 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nCattermole remained captain at the start of the [[2011\u201312 Sunderland A.F.C. season|2011\u201312 season]] and received yellow cards in the first two games, against Liverpool and Newcastle. He then fell out of favour, with his next full match not coming until 5 November, in a defeat at Manchester United. Following Bruce's sacking and the appointment of [[Martin O'Neill]] as his successor, it was suggested Cattermole might lose the captaincy, especially after he and [[Nicklas Bendtner]] were arrested for allegedly damaging cars in Newcastle city centre. However, he led the team on his first appearance under O'Neill, a 3\u20132 win at QPR. Cattermole had arguably two of his best performances for the Black Cats in their 1\u20130 win over Manchester City on New Years Day 2012 and a 4\u20131 win at Wigan two days later. After the victory over Manchester City, O'Neill told his captain: \"Well done, absolutely brilliant. You've got a heart like a lion\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tribalfootball.com/articles/sunderland-captain-cattermole-oneill-says-ive-heart-lion-2658831 |title=Sunderland captain Cattermole: O'Neill says I've heart of lion |publisher=Tribal Football |date=27 January 2012 |accessdate=16 October 2013}}</ref> The skipper also put in another excellent defensive performance in the FA Cup fifth-round game against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] on 18 February. Cattermole and his teammates constantly pressed the Arsenal players when they had possession, forcing mistakes and with counter-attacking football, the ''Black Cats'' won 2\u20130.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2012/feb/18/sunderland-arsenal-fa-cup-match-report|title=Sunderland's Kieran Richardson puts seal on Arsenal's week of misery|newspaper=The Guardian|location=London|first=Louise|last=Taylor|date=18 February 2012|accessdate=31 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Flickr - Ronnie Macdonald - Pre match 3.jpg|thumb|upright|200px|Cattermole (right) posing for a pre-match photo before facing [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] in August 2012]]\n\nOn 4 March 2012, Cattermole was booked in the first minute of the [[Tyne-Wear derby]] for a challenge on Newcastle's [[Cheick Tiot\u00e9]]. He received a red card at the conclusion of the match after confronting referee [[Mike Dean (referee)|Mike Dean]]. Martin O'Neill described Cattermole's sending off as \"foolish\" but claimed Newcastle were \"lucky\" to finish with 11 players.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17250376 |title=Cattermole sending-off foolish \u2013 Martin O'Neill |website=BBC Sport |date=4 March 2012 |accessdate=31 May 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306233655/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17250376 |archivedate=6 March 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Cattermole received a four-match ban for the incident.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sunderland's Lee Cattermole and St\u00e9phane Sess\u00e8gnon to miss Everton tie|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2012/mar/06/sunderland-cattermole-sessegnon-everton-fa-cup|newspaper=The Guardian|date=6 March 2012|accessdate=23 April 2012|location=London|first=Louise|last=Taylor}}</ref> During his ban, reports suggested that O'Neill would strip Cattermole of the captaincy because of his behaviour at the Tyne-Wear Derby match but O'Neill denied the claims.<ref>{{cite news|title=Careless Cattermole keeps captaincy despite derby day dismissal|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2112672/Lee-Cattermole-stay-Sunderland-captain.html|newspaper=Daily Mail|date=9 March 2012|accessdate=23 April 2012|location=London}}</ref> After serving his ban, Cattermole made his return for Sunderland on 27 March in the FA Cup quarter-final replay against Everton, a match Sunderland went on to lose 2\u20130. Through 73 games for Sunderland in all competitions, Cattermole had been booked 32 times and received four red cards.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11695/7784239/cattermole-set-for-new-deal |title=Cattermole set for new deal| publisher=Sky Sports |date=28 May 2012 |accessdate=2 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe start of the [[2013\u201314 Sunderland A.F.C. season|2013\u201314 season]] saw Cattermole replaced as captain by [[John O'Shea]] and his number 6 shirt handed to new signing [[Cabral (footballer)|Cabral]]. Cattermole was assigned the number 33 jersey. He scored his first league goal for Sunderland in a 5\u20131 loss to [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] at [[White Hart Lane]] on 7 April 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/26814762|title=Tottenham Hotspur 5\u20131 Sunderland|website=BBC Sport|first=Saj|last=Chowdhury|date=7 April 2014|accessdate=31 May 2017}}</ref>\n[[File:Sunderland 3 Chelsea 2 Cattermole Matic.jpg|thumb|left|160px|Cattermole captaining Sunderland against [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] in May 2016]]\nCattermole regained his number 6 shirt at the start of the [[2014\u201315 Sunderland A.F.C. season|2014\u201315 season]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.safc.com/news/club-news/2014/august/squad-numbers-confirmed |title=Squad numbers confirmed |publisher=Sunderland A.F.C. |date=15 August 2014 |archiveurl=https://www.safc.com/news/club-news/2014/august/squad-numbers-confirmed |archivedate=19 August 2014}}</ref> and scored Sunderland's first goal of the season, with a 25-yard strike which he described as being 'the best goal he has ever scored',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.safc.com/news/team-news/2014/august/rodwell-happy-with-point |title=Rodwell looking to build on point |publisher=Sunderland A.F.C. |first=Oscar |last=Chamberlain |date=16 August 2014 |accessdate=31 May 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150708191856/https://www.safc.com/news/team-news/2014/august/rodwell-happy-with-point |archivedate=8 July 2015}}</ref> in a 2\u20132 draw away to [[West Bromwich Albion F.C|West Brom]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/28718388 |title=West Bromwich Albion 2\u20132 Sunderland |website=BBC Sport |first=Jamie |last=Strickland |date=15 August 2014}}</ref> On 2 July 2015, Cattermole signed a five-year contract extension with Sunderland, committing his future to the club until 2021.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.safc.com/news/team-news/2015/july/cattermole-pens-new-deal |title=Cattermole pens new deal |publisher=Sunderland A.F.C. |first=Stuart |last=Vose |date=2 July 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150703030151/https://www.safc.com/news/team-news/2015/july/cattermole-pens-new-deal |archivedate=3 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn the opening day of the [[2015\u201316 Sunderland A.F.C. season|2015\u201316 season]], Cattermole captained Sunderland against [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] at the [[King Power Stadium]], but was substituted by [[Dick Advocaat]] after 30 minutes, with his side 3\u20130 down and Cattermole having conceded a penalty. Sunderland would go on to lose 4\u20132.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/33744669|title=Leicester City 4\u20132 Sunderland|website=BBC Sport|first=Aimee|last=Lewis|date=8 August 2015|accessdate=31 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nAfter missing most of the [[2016\u201317 Sunderland A.F.C. season|2016\u201317 season]] through injury, Cattermole returned to the first team late in the campaign and earned praise from Sunderland fans for his performance against Arsenal at the [[Emirates Stadium]] on 16 May 2017 as the ''Black Cats'' were defeated 2\u20130 thanks to a [[Hat-trick|brace]] from [[Alexis S\u00e1nchez]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hitc.com/en-gb/2017/05/17/sunderland-fans-react-on-twitter-to-lee-cattermoles-performanc-1/|title=Sunderland fans react on Twitter to Lee Cattermole's performance against Arsenal|publisher=Here is the City|first=John|last=Verrall|date=17 May 2017|accessdate=31 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/39853089|title=Arsenal 2\u20130 Sunderland|website=BBC Sport|first=Jonathan|last=Jurejko|date=16 May 2017|accessdate=31 May 2017}}</ref> Cattermole suffered relegation with Sunderland as the club finished bottom of the table on just 24 points, ending their ten-year stint in the top flight.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.the42.ie/david-moyes-resigns-3403236-May2017/|title=24 points later: David Moyes resigns as manager of relegated Sunderland|website=The42|publisher=[[TheJournal.ie]]|first=Niall|last=Kelly|date=22 May 2017|accessdate=31 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 March 2019, during the [[EFL Trophy]] final against [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]], Cattermole's penalty was saved by [[Craig MacGillivray (footballer)|Craig MacGillivray]] in a 5\u20134 loss on penalties for Sunderland following a 2\u20132 draw after extra time.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47709134 |title=Checkatrade Trophy final: Portsmouth 2\u20132 Sunderland (aet, 5\u20134 on pens) |date=31 March 2019 |accessdate=2 April 2019}}</ref> On 1 July 2019, it was announced that Cattermole would leave Sunderland after having spent 10 years at the club. Cattermole explained in the announcement that \"it is the right time to find a new challenge\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.safc.com:443/news/team-news/2019/july/cattermole-announcement |title=Cattermole departs |publisher=Sunderland A.F.C. |date=1 July 2019 |accessdate=2 July 2019}}</ref> He subsequently had a trial with [[Eredivisie]] side [[VVV-Venlo]] in August.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.vvv-venlo.nl/nl/vvv-venlo/nieuws/lee_cattermole_sluit_aan_bij_training |title=Lee Cattermole sluit aan bij training |publisher=VVV-Venlo |date=15 August 2019 |accessdate=15 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49356043 |title=Lee Cattermole: Former Sunderland midfielder joins Dutch side VVV Venlo on trial |publisher=BBC Sport |date=15 August 2019 |accessdate=15 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n===VVV-Venlo===\nOn 22 August 2019, Cattermole signed a year-long contract with Dutch side [[VVV-Venlo]], joining on a free transfer.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.vvv-venlo.nl/nl/vvv-venlo/nieuws/lee_cattermole_per_direct_vvver |title=Lee Cattermole per direct VVV'er |publisher=VVV Venlo |date=22 August 2019 |accessdate=22 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nCattermole received his first call-up to the [[England national under-21 football team|England under-21 squad]] for the October 2006 play-offs against [[Germany national under-21 football team|Germany]].\nCattermole scored his first international goal and the first goal of the U-21 European Championships on 15 June 2009 against [[Finland national under-21 football team|Finland]]. The goal was set up by Aston Villa striker [[Gabriel Agbonlahor]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/england-u21-vs-finland-u21/report/20080|title=England U21 2\u20131 Finland U21|publisher=Sky Sports|first=Chris|last=Burton|date=16 June 2009|accessdate=31 May 2017}}</ref> Cattermole went on to score his third in an England shirt when they came from behind to defeat [[Macedonia national under-21 football team|Macedonia U21s]] in a 2\u20131 win with a goal in the 83rd minute sealing the victory after an impressive goal from [[Freddie Sears]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/international/sears-and-cattermole-get-england-u21-campaign-off-to-winning-start-1781933.html|title=Sears and Cattermole get England U21 campaign off to winning start|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|date=4 September 2009|accessdate=31 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn December 2008, Cattermole was given a three-year pub ban across the Stockton borough. He was added to the [[PubWatch]] blacklist of troublemakers after being arrested for disorder during a night out in [[Yarm]]. Police were called by door staff at about 11:40&nbsp;pm and Cattermole was subsequently arrested.<ref>{{cite news|first=Naomi |last=Corrigan |url=http://www.gazettelive.co.uk/news/local-news/footballers-cattermole-bates-given-pub-3724820 |title=Footballers Cattermole and Bates given pub ban |newspaper=Teesside Gazette |location=Middlesbrough |date=17 December 2008 |accessdate=16 October 2013}}</ref>\nIn March 2011, it was announced that Cattermole's ban would be extended to December 2012 after a unanimous vote by the members of PubWatch. Cattermole declined to comment on these matters.<ref>{{cite news |first=Steve |last=White |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/top-stories/2011/03/16/sunderland-footballer-lee-cattermole-s-pub-ban-extended-115875-22992173/ |title=Sunderland footballer Lee Cattermole's pub ban extended |newspaper=[[Daily Mirror]] |date=16 March 2011 |accessdate=16 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nFollowing a night out with teammates, Cattermole was arrested on 6 December 2011 along with then teammate [[Nicklas Bendtner]] and charged with damaging five cars on Stowell Street in Newcastle, close to St James' Park. On 25 March 2012, the case at Newcastle Magistrates Court was adjourned to be brought back before the same court on 16 April 2012. Charges against Bendtner were subsequently dropped.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/local-news/lee-cattermole-court-case-adjourned-1362294 |title=Lee Cattermole court case is adjourned in Newcastle |newspaper=[[Evening Chronicle]] |location=Newcastle upon Tyne |date=26 March 2012 |accessdate=16 October 2013}}</ref> Cattermole accepted a conditional caution and paid over \u00a34,000 in damages.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2012/apr/27/sunderland-captain-lee-cattermole-vandalising-cars | newspaper=The Guardian | location=London |title=Sunderland captain Lee Cattermole admits to vandalising cars | date=27 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{updated|match played 30 April 2019}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.soccerbase.com/players/player.sd?player_id=43076|title=Lee Cattermole|work=Soccerbase|publisher=Centurycomm|accessdate=6 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+ Appearances a