rland A.F.C. season|2017\u201318]]\n|[[EFL Championship|Championship]]\n|35||1||0||0||0||0||0||0||35||1\n|-\n|[[2018\u201319 Sunderland A.F.C. season|2018\u201319]]\n|[[EFL League One|League One]]\n|29||7||1||0||1||0||2{{efn|Appearances in [[EFL Trophy]]}}||0||33||7\n|-\n!colspan=2|Total\n!233!!10!!9!!0!!14!!0!!2!!0!!258!!10\n|-\n!colspan=3|Career total\n!335!!14!!23!!1!!19!!1!!7!!0!!384!!16\n|}\n\n{{notelist}}\n\n==Honours==\n'''Middlesbrough'''\n*[[UEFA Cup]] runner-up: [[2005\u201306 UEFA Cup|2005\u201306]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/4751467.stm |title=Middlesbrough 0\u20134 Sevilla |website=BBC Sport |date=10 May 2006 |accessdate=7 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n'''Sunderland'''\n*[[Football League Cup]] runner-up: [[2013\u201314 Football League Cup|2013\u201314]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/26311649 |title=Manchester City 3\u20131 Sunderland |first=Phil |last=McNulty |website=BBC Sport |date=2 March 2014 |accessdate=7 May 2019}}</ref>\n*[[EFL Trophy]] runner-up: [[2018\u201319 EFL Trophy|2018\u201319]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47709134 |title=Portsmouth 2\u20132 Sunderland |first=Adam |last=Williams |website=BBC Sport |date=31 March 2019 |accessdate=7 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n'''England U21'''\n*[[UEFA European Under-21 Championship]] runner-up: [[2009 UEFA European Under-21 Championship|2009]]<ref>{{cite new |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/8122457.stm |title=Germany U21 4\u20130 England U21 |first=David |last=McIntyre |website=BBC Sport |date=29 June 2009 |accessdate=7 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n'''Individual'''\n*North East Football Writers' Association's Player of the Year: 2014<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.sunderlandecho.com/sport/sunderland-afc/cattermole-beats-colback-to-be-named-player-of-year-by-football-writers-1-6947148 |title=Cattermole beats Colback to be named player of year by football writers |newspaper=[[Sunderland Echo]] |first=Chris |last=Young |date=11 November 2014 |accessdate=31 May 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150114203207/http://www.sunderlandecho.com/sport/sunderland-afc/cattermole-beats-colback-to-be-named-player-of-year-by-football-writers-1-6947148 |archive-date=14 January 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n\n{{VVV-Venlo squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cattermole, Lee}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Stockton-on-Tees]]\n[[Category:Footballers from County Durham]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:England youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:England under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Middlesbrough F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Wigan Athletic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Sunderland A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:VVV-Venlo players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}}\n{{Infobox football biography\n| name           = Lee Cattermole\n| image          = Lee Cattermole.jpg\n| image_size     = 200\n| caption        = Cattermole playing for Sunderland in 2011\n| fullname       = Lee Barry Cattermole<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.premierleague.com/news/84136 |title=Squads for 2016/17 Premier League confirmed |publisher=Premier League |date=1 September 2016 |accessdate=31 May 2017}}</ref>\n| birth_date     = {{birth date and age|1988|3|21|df=y}}<ref name=\"pl profile\">{{cite web|url=https://www.premierleague.com/players/2949/Lee-Cattermole/overview |title=Lee Cattermole |publisher=Premier League |accessdate=31 May 2017}}</ref>\n| birth_place    = [[Stockton-on-Tees]], England\n| height         = {{convert|1.78|m|order=flip}}<ref name=\"pl profile\"/>\n| position       = [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|Defensive midfielder]]\n| currentclub    = [[VVV-Venlo]]\n| clubnumber     = 31\n| youthyears1    = 1998\u20132005\n| youthclubs1    = [[Middlesbrough F.C. Reserves and Academy|Middlesbrough]]\n| years1         = 2005\u20132008\n| clubs1         = [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]]\n| caps1          = 69\n| goals1         = 3\n| years2         = 2008\u20132009\n| clubs2         = [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]]\n| caps2          = 33\n| goals2         = 1\n| years3         = 2009\u20132019\n| clubs3         = [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]]\n| caps3          = 233\n| goals3         = 10\n| years4         = 2019\u2013\n| clubs4         = [[VVV-Venlo]]\n| caps4          = 11\n| goals4         = 0\n| nationalyears1 = 2003\n| nationalteam1  = [[England national under-16 football team|England U16]]\n| nationalcaps1  = 1\n| nationalgoals1 = 0\n| nationalyears2 = 2004\n| nationalteam2  = [[England national under-17 football team|England U17]]\n| nationalcaps2  = 4\n| nationalgoals2 = 0\n| nationalyears3 = 2005\n| nationalteam3  = [[England national under-18 football team|England U18]]\n| nationalcaps3  = 1\n| nationalgoals3 = 0\n| nationalyears4 = 2006\n| nationalteam4  = [[England national under-19 football team|England U19]]\n| nationalcaps4  = 1\n| nationalgoals4 = 0\n| nationalyears5 = 2007\u20132010\n| nationalteam5  = [[England national under-21 football team|England U21]]\n| nationalcaps5  = 16\n| nationalgoals5 = 3\n| club-update = 12:31, 14 February   2020 (UTC)\n| nationalteam-update = \n}}\n'''Lee Barry Cattermole ''' (born 21 March 1988) is an English professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Midfielder#Central midfielder|central midfielder]] for Dutch club [[VVV-Venlo]].\n\nAn [[England national football team|England]] youth product, Cattermole has earned a reputation as a tough-tackling midfielder due to his lengthy disciplinary record. He began his professional career at [[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]] in 2005, having progressed through the [[Middlesbrough F.C. Reserves and Academy|club's academy]]. After making his debut for the club in January 2006, he became a regular player, and at the age of 18 years and 47 days was the youngest man to captain Middlesbrough where he made 91 appearances and scored four goals. He switched to [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]] in July 2008. Cattermole quickly became a regular for Wigan, amassing 35 appearances in the 2008\u201309 season. After attracting interest from other Premier League clubs, he joined [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] in August 2009. Despite a few injury problems early in his spell at the club, manager [[Steve Bruce]] selected him as captain for the start of the 2010\u201311 season, a role he would hold for three seasons, until [[Paolo di Canio]] gave [[John O'Shea]] the role prior to the start of the 2013\u201314 season.\n\nInternationally, Cattermole represented [[England national football team|England]] at [[England national under-16 football team|under-16]], [[England national under-17 football team|under-17]], [[England national under-18 football team|under-18]], [[England national under-19 football team|under-19]] and [[England national under-21 football team|under-21]] levels.\n\n==Club career==\n\n===Middlesbrough===\nA product of the Middlesbrough [[Middlesbrough F.C. Reserves and Academy|youth academy]], Cattermole made his debut in the [[Tyne-Tees derby]] against [[Newcastle United F.C.|Newcastle United]] on 2 January 2006, playing the full 90 minutes in a match that finished 2\u20132 in which the England youth international received the Man of the Match award.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mfc.premiumtv.co.uk/page/Squad/ProfilesDetail/0,,1~35989,00.html |title=Lee Cattermole |publisher=Middlesbrough F.C. |accessdate=13 August 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080409124523/http://www.mfc.premiumtv.co.uk/page/Squad/ProfilesDetail/0,,1~35989,00.html |archivedate=9 April 2008}}</ref> Manager [[Steve McClaren]] later hailed his performance stating, \"When we needed people to stand up and be counted, it took a 17-year-old to bring everyone together.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11680/2366007/catt-has-mcclaren-purring |title=Catt has McClaren purring |publisher=[[Sky Sports]] |first=Graeme |last=Bailey |date=4 February 2006 |accessdate=13 August 2009}}</ref>\n\nAfter a 4\u20130 home defeat to [[Aston Villa F.C.|Aston Villa]], he was captured on camera in tears and had to be consoled by captain [[Gareth Southgate]].<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.gazettelive.co.uk/boro-fc/boro-fc-news/tm_headline=boro-s-homegrown-heroes--lee-cattermole&method=full&objectid=17987895&siteid=109975-name_page.html |title=Lee Cattermole |newspaper=[[Teesside Gazette]] |location=Middlesbrough |date=25 October 2006 |first=Philip |last=Tallentire |accessdate=13 August 2009 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091227070741/http://www.gazettelive.co.uk/boro-fc/boro-fc-news/tm_headline%3Dboro-s-homegrown-heroes--lee-cattermole%26method%3Dfull%26objectid%3D17987895%26siteid%3D109975-name_page.html |archivedate=27 December 2009 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> However, after this game the team went on to win seven out of their next eight games, advancing to the quarter-finals of both the [[FA Cup|FA]] and [[UEFA Cup|UEFA]] cups and defeating [[Premier League]] champions [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] 3\u20130, only their second league defeat of the season.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.soccerbase.com/results2.sd?teamid=1697&seasonid=135 |title=Middlesbro 2005/2006 results and fixtures |work=Soccerbase |publisher=Centurycomm |accessdate=13 August 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060219045940/http://www.soccerbase.com/results2.sd?teamid=1697&seasonid=135|archivedate=19 February 2006}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.soccerbase.com/results2.sd?teamid=536&seasonid=135 |title=Chelsea 2005/2006 results and fixtures |work=Soccerbase |publisher=Centurycomm |accessdate=13 August 2009|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060419202138/http://www.soccerbase.com/results2.sd?teamid=536&seasonid=135|archivedate=19 April 2006}}</ref> Cattermole scored his first league goal for Middlesbrough on 2 April, in a 1\u20130 victory away at [[Manchester City F.C.|Manchester City]],<ref>{{cite news |title=Man City 0\u20131 Middlesbrough |website=[[BBC Sport]] |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_prem/4853690.stm |date=2 April 2006 |accessdate=13 August 2009}}</ref> and played for Middlesbrough in the [[2006 UEFA Cup Final]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.uefa.com/uefaeuropaleague/season=2005/matches/round=2214/match=84102/postmatch/report/index.html |title=Sevilla run away with the trophy |publisher=[[UEFA]] |first=Michael |last=Harrold |date=11 May 2006 |accessdate=13 August 2009}}</ref>\n\nCattermole became Middlesbrough's youngest-ever captain aged 18 years and 47 days when he skippered the side in their 1\u20130 defeat away against [[Fulham F.C.|Fulham]] on 7 May 2006. During the game, Middlesbrough's oldest-ever player, [[Colin Cooper]], came on as a substitute and Cattermole sportingly gave the captain's armband, without instruction, to Cooper who was playing his last game before retirement.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.gazettelive.co.uk/sport/football/football-news/fulham-1-boro-0---3772571|title=Fulham 1, Boro 0 \u2013 Young guns are blazing|newspaper=Teesside Gazette|location=Middlesbrough|date=8 May 2006|accessdate=31 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2008/nov/22/wigan-athletic|title=Cattermole makes arresting case for learning his trade the hard way|newspaper=[[The Guardian]]|location=London|first=Daniel|last=Taylor|date=22 November 2008|accessdate=31 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 20 October 2006, Cattermole signed a new four-year deal to keep him at Middlesbrough until 2010.<ref>{{cite web|title=Boro prodigy Cattermole pens four-year deal |publisher=[[ESPN FC]] |url=http://www.espnfc.com/story/386532 |date=20 October 2006 |accessdate=6 February 2007}}</ref>\n\n===Wigan Athletic===\nOn 29 July 2008, Cattermole signed for [[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]] on a three-year deal in a transfer worth [[pound sterling|\u00a3]]3.5&nbsp;million.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/teams/wigan-athletic/2469945/Wigan-sign-Lee-Cattermole-from-Middlesbrough-on-three-year-deal.html|title=Wigan sign Lee Cattermole from Middlesbrough on three-year deal|last=Lawless|first=Matt|date=29 July 2008|work=The Daily Telegraph|access-date=2 April 2019|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235}}</ref> He made his debut against [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] in a 2\u20131 defeat. Cattermole scored his first goal for Wigan in a 4\u20131 League Cup win over Ipswich Town on 24 September 2008.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/league_cup/7626823.stm|title=Ipswich 1\u20134 Wigan|website=BBC Sport|date=24 September 2008 |accessdate=8 November 2009}}</ref> He then scored his first league goal in a 3\u20130 home win over [[Blackburn Rovers F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]] on 13 December 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport2/hi/football/eng_prem/7763502.stm |title=Wigan 3\u20130 Blackburn |website=BBC Sport |first=Julian |last=Shea |date=13 December 2008 |accessdate=15 September 2009}}</ref> On 4 March, he was given a straight red card, his second of the season, for a reckless challenge on [[Scott Parker]] in the home defeat by West Ham.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2009/mar/04/premierleague-wiganathletic|title=Cole the poacher is sent packing|newspaper=The Guardian|location=London|first=Richard|last=Jolly|date=4 March 2009}}</ref> Despite being tied to a three-year deal, Cattermole's highly impressive season with Wigan resulted in constant speculation that he was a target for other clubs.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-1195600/Wigan-battler-Cattermole-attracts-Liverpool-Spurs-Sunderland.html|title=Wigan battler Cattermole attracts interest from Liverpool, Spurs and Sunderland|newspaper=[[Daily Mail]]|location=London|date=26 June 2009|accessdate=31 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Sunderland===\n[[File:Cattermole and Craig Gardner.jpg|thumb|upright|Cattermole (left) playing for Sunderland in 2011 alongside Craig Gardner (right)]]\nOn 12 August 2009, it was announced that Cattermole had completed a medical at [[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]] and signed for a fee of \u00a36&nbsp;million. The midfielder joined the club on a four-year contract, reuniting with former Wigan coach [[Steve Bruce]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11682/5487063/black-cats-swoop-for-cattermole |publisher=Sky Sports |title=Black Cats swoop for Cattermole |date=13 August 2009}}</ref> He made his debut in a 1\u20130 win over [[Bolton Wanderers F.C.|Bolton Wanderers]], in which he won Sunderland's Man of the Match award. He then in the next few games of the season became popular amongst the fans despite missing several games with a heel injury. On 17 October 2009, he injured his knee in the win over Liverpool and was ruled out for twelve weeks.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sunderland's Lee Cattermole faces three months out with knee injury|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2009/oct/20/lee-cattermole-sunderland-injury-bruce|newspaper=The Guardian|location=London|date=20 October 2009}}</ref> He returned as a second-half substitute for [[Jordan Henderson]] on 15 December in a 2\u20130 loss against [[Aston Villa]]. He then played the full match and captained the side in the 4\u20133 defeat by Manchester City.\n\nOn the eve of the 2010\u201311 season, Cattermole was selected by manager Bruce as the replacement captain after [[Lorik Cana]]'s departure. He was also handed the vacant number 6 shirt. He received a red card in the first game of the season against [[Birmingham City F.C.|Birmingham City]] for a second bookable offence. Bruce later referred to referee Anthony Taylor as 'out of his depth'. Cattermole played most of the 90 minutes in Sunderland's 3\u20130 away win against Chelsea, coming off in added time in the second half and was pivotal in the victory. He then earned the Man of the Match award for his performance at home to West Ham, a game which Sunderland won 1\u20130. Cattermole's tough tackling style has put him into troublesome situations with referees. Bruce, despite backing Cattermole as club captain, said that his disciplinary record must improve. Again, Cattermole suffered an injury-hit season, making 24 appearances in total (two more than the previous season).<ref>{{Soccerbase season|43076|2010|name=Lee Cattermole|accessdate=31 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Soccerbase season|43076|2009|name=Lee Cattermole|accessdate=31 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nCattermole remained captain at the start of the [[2011\u201312 Sunderland A.F.C. season|2011\u201312 season]] and received yellow cards in the first two games, against Liverpool and Newcastle. He then fell out of favour, with his next full match not coming until 5 November, in a defeat at Manchester United. Following Bruce's sacking and the appointment of [[Martin O'Neill]] as his successor, it was suggested Cattermole might lose the captaincy, especially after he and [[Nicklas Bendtner]] were arrested for allegedly damaging cars in Newcastle city centre. However, he led the team on his first appearance under O'Neill, a 3\u20132 win at QPR. Cattermole had arguably two of his best performances for the Black Cats in their 1\u20130 win over Manchester City on New Years Day 2012 and a 4\u20131 win at Wigan two days later. After the victory over Manchester City, O'Neill told his captain: \"Well done, absolutely brilliant. You've got a heart like a lion\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.tribalfootball.com/articles/sunderland-captain-cattermole-oneill-says-ive-heart-lion-2658831 |title=Sunderland captain Cattermole: O'Neill says I've heart of lion |publisher=Tribal Football |date=27 January 2012 |accessdate=16 October 2013}}</ref> The skipper also put in another excellent defensive performance in the FA Cup fifth-round game against [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] on 18 February. Cattermole and his teammates constantly pressed the Arsenal players when they had possession, forcing mistakes and with counter-attacking football, the ''Black Cats'' won 2\u20130.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2012/feb/18/sunderland-arsenal-fa-cup-match-report|title=Sunderland's Kieran Richardson puts seal on Arsenal's week of misery|newspaper=The Guardian|location=London|first=Louise|last=Taylor|date=18 February 2012|accessdate=31 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Flickr - Ronnie Macdonald - Pre match 3.jpg|thumb|upright|200px|Cattermole (right) posing for a pre-match photo before facing [[Arsenal F.C.|Arsenal]] in August 2012]]\n\nOn 4 March 2012, Cattermole was booked in the first minute of the [[Tyne-Wear derby]] for a challenge on Newcastle's [[Cheick Tiot\u00e9]]. He received a red card at the conclusion of the match after confronting referee [[Mike Dean (referee)|Mike Dean]]. Martin O'Neill described Cattermole's sending off as \"foolish\" but claimed Newcastle were \"lucky\" to finish with 11 players.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17250376 |title=Cattermole sending-off foolish \u2013 Martin O'Neill |website=BBC Sport |date=4 March 2012 |accessdate=31 May 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120306233655/https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/0/football/17250376 |archivedate=6 March 2012 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Cattermole received a four-match ban for the incident.<ref>{{cite news|title=Sunderland's Lee Cattermole and St\u00e9phane Sess\u00e8gnon to miss Everton tie|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2012/mar/06/sunderland-cattermole-sessegnon-everton-fa-cup|newspaper=The Guardian|date=6 March 2012|accessdate=23 April 2012|location=London|first=Louise|last=Taylor}}</ref> During his ban, reports suggested that O'Neill would strip Cattermole of the captaincy because of his behaviour at the Tyne-Wear Derby match but O'Neill denied the claims.<ref>{{cite news|title=Careless Cattermole keeps captaincy despite derby day dismissal|url=http://www.dailymail.co.uk/sport/football/article-2112672/Lee-Cattermole-stay-Sunderland-captain.html|newspaper=Daily Mail|date=9 March 2012|accessdate=23 April 2012|location=London}}</ref> After serving his ban, Cattermole made his return for Sunderland on 27 March in the FA Cup quarter-final replay against Everton, a match Sunderland went on to lose 2\u20130. Through 73 games for Sunderland in all competitions, Cattermole had been booked 32 times and received four red cards.<ref>{{cite web| url=http://www.skysports.com/football/news/11695/7784239/cattermole-set-for-new-deal |title=Cattermole set for new deal| publisher=Sky Sports |date=28 May 2012 |accessdate=2 June 2013}}</ref>\n\nThe start of the [[2013\u201314 Sunderland A.F.C. season|2013\u201314 season]] saw Cattermole replaced as captain by [[John O'Shea]] and his number 6 shirt handed to new signing [[Cabral (footballer)|Cabral]]. Cattermole was assigned the number 33 jersey. He scored his first league goal for Sunderland in a 5\u20131 loss to [[Tottenham Hotspur F.C.|Tottenham Hotspur]] at [[White Hart Lane]] on 7 April 2014.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/26814762|title=Tottenham Hotspur 5\u20131 Sunderland|website=BBC Sport|first=Saj|last=Chowdhury|date=7 April 2014|accessdate=31 May 2017}}</ref>\n[[File:Sunderland 3 Chelsea 2 Cattermole Matic.jpg|thumb|left|160px|Cattermole captaining Sunderland against [[Chelsea F.C.|Chelsea]] in May 2016]]\nCattermole regained his number 6 shirt at the start of the [[2014\u201315 Sunderland A.F.C. season|2014\u201315 season]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.safc.com/news/club-news/2014/august/squad-numbers-confirmed |title=Squad numbers confirmed |publisher=Sunderland A.F.C. |date=15 August 2014 |archiveurl=https://www.safc.com/news/club-news/2014/august/squad-numbers-confirmed |archivedate=19 August 2014}}</ref> and scored Sunderland's first goal of the season, with a 25-yard strike which he described as being 'the best goal he has ever scored',<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.safc.com/news/team-news/2014/august/rodwell-happy-with-point |title=Rodwell looking to build on point |publisher=Sunderland A.F.C. |first=Oscar |last=Chamberlain |date=16 August 2014 |accessdate=31 May 2017 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150708191856/https://www.safc.com/news/team-news/2014/august/rodwell-happy-with-point |archivedate=8 July 2015}}</ref> in a 2\u20132 draw away to [[West Bromwich Albion F.C|West Brom]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/28718388 |title=West Bromwich Albion 2\u20132 Sunderland |website=BBC Sport |first=Jamie |last=Strickland |date=15 August 2014}}</ref> On 2 July 2015, Cattermole signed a five-year contract extension with Sunderland, committing his future to the club until 2021.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.safc.com/news/team-news/2015/july/cattermole-pens-new-deal |title=Cattermole pens new deal |publisher=Sunderland A.F.C. |first=Stuart |last=Vose |date=2 July 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150703030151/https://www.safc.com/news/team-news/2015/july/cattermole-pens-new-deal |archivedate=3 July 2015}}</ref>\n\nOn the opening day of the [[2015\u201316 Sunderland A.F.C. season|2015\u201316 season]], Cattermole captained Sunderland against [[Leicester City F.C.|Leicester City]] at the [[King Power Stadium]], but was substituted by [[Dick Advocaat]] after 30 minutes, with his side 3\u20130 down and Cattermole having conceded a penalty. Sunderland would go on to lose 4\u20132.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/33744669|title=Leicester City 4\u20132 Sunderland|website=BBC Sport|first=Aimee|last=Lewis|date=8 August 2015|accessdate=31 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nAfter missing most of the [[2016\u201317 Sunderland A.F.C. season|2016\u201317 season]] through injury, Cattermole returned to the first team late in the campaign and earned praise from Sunderland fans for his performance against Arsenal at the [[Emirates Stadium]] on 16 May 2017 as the ''Black Cats'' were defeated 2\u20130 thanks to a [[Hat-trick|brace]] from [[Alexis S\u00e1nchez]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hitc.com/en-gb/2017/05/17/sunderland-fans-react-on-twitter-to-lee-cattermoles-performanc-1/|title=Sunderland fans react on Twitter to Lee Cattermole's performance against Arsenal|publisher=Here is the City|first=John|last=Verrall|date=17 May 2017|accessdate=31 May 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.com/sport/football/39853089|title=Arsenal 2\u20130 Sunderland|website=BBC Sport|first=Jonathan|last=Jurejko|date=16 May 2017|accessdate=31 May 2017}}</ref> Cattermole suffered relegation with Sunderland as the club finished bottom of the table on just 24 points, ending their ten-year stint in the top flight.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.the42.ie/david-moyes-resigns-3403236-May2017/|title=24 points later: David Moyes resigns as manager of relegated Sunderland|website=The42|publisher=[[TheJournal.ie]]|first=Niall|last=Kelly|date=22 May 2017|accessdate=31 May 2017}}</ref>\n\nOn 31 March 2019, during the [[EFL Trophy]] final against [[Portsmouth F.C.|Portsmouth]], Cattermole's penalty was saved by [[Craig MacGillivray (footballer)|Craig MacGillivray]] in a 5\u20134 loss on penalties for Sunderland following a 2\u20132 draw after extra time.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47709134 |title=Checkatrade Trophy final: Portsmouth 2\u20132 Sunderland (aet, 5\u20134 on pens) |date=31 March 2019 |accessdate=2 April 2019}}</ref> On 1 July 2019, it was announced that Cattermole would leave Sunderland after having spent 10 years at the club. Cattermole explained in the announcement that \"it is the right time to find a new challenge\".<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.safc.com:443/news/team-news/2019/july/cattermole-announcement |title=Cattermole departs |publisher=Sunderland A.F.C. |date=1 July 2019 |accessdate=2 July 2019}}</ref> He subsequently had a trial with [[Eredivisie]] side [[VVV-Venlo]] in August.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.vvv-venlo.nl/nl/vvv-venlo/nieuws/lee_cattermole_sluit_aan_bij_training |title=Lee Cattermole sluit aan bij training |publisher=VVV-Venlo |date=15 August 2019 |accessdate=15 August 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/49356043 |title=Lee Cattermole: Former Sunderland midfielder joins Dutch side VVV Venlo on trial |publisher=BBC Sport |date=15 August 2019 |accessdate=15 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n===VVV-Venlo===\nOn 22 August 2019, Cattermole signed a year-long contract with Dutch side [[VVV-Venlo]], joining on a free transfer.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.vvv-venlo.nl/nl/vvv-venlo/nieuws/lee_cattermole_per_direct_vvver |title=Lee Cattermole per direct VVV'er |publisher=VVV Venlo |date=22 August 2019 |accessdate=22 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\nCattermole received his first call-up to the [[England national under-21 football team|England under-21 squad]] for the October 2006 play-offs against [[Germany national under-21 football team|Germany]].\nCattermole scored his first international goal and the first goal of the U-21 European Championships on 15 June 2009 against [[Finland national under-21 football team|Finland]]. The goal was set up by Aston Villa striker [[Gabriel Agbonlahor]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skysports.com/football/england-u21-vs-finland-u21/report/20080|title=England U21 2\u20131 Finland U21|publisher=Sky Sports|first=Chris|last=Burton|date=16 June 2009|accessdate=31 May 2017}}</ref> Cattermole went on to score his third in an England shirt when they came from behind to defeat [[Macedonia national under-21 football team|Macedonia U21s]] in a 2\u20131 win with a goal in the 83rd minute sealing the victory after an impressive goal from [[Freddie Sears]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/international/sears-and-cattermole-get-england-u21-campaign-off-to-winning-start-1781933.html|title=Sears and Cattermole get England U21 campaign off to winning start|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|date=4 September 2009|accessdate=31 May 2017}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nIn December 2008, Cattermole was given a three-year pub ban across the Stockton borough. He was added to the [[PubWatch]] blacklist of troublemakers after being arrested for disorder during a night out in [[Yarm]]. Police were called by door staff at about 11:40&nbsp;pm and Cattermole was subsequently arrested.<ref>{{cite news|first=Naomi |last=Corrigan |url=http://www.gazettelive.co.uk/news/local-news/footballers-cattermole-bates-given-pub-3724820 |title=Footballers Cattermole and Bates given pub ban |newspaper=Teesside Gazette |location=Middlesbrough |date=17 December 2008 |accessdate=16 October 2013}}</ref>\nIn March 2011, it was announced that Cattermole's ban would be extended to December 2012 after a unanimous vote by the members of PubWatch. Cattermole declined to comment on these matters.<ref>{{cite news |first=Steve |last=White |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/news/top-stories/2011/03/16/sunderland-footballer-lee-cattermole-s-pub-ban-extended-115875-22992173/ |title=Sunderland footballer Lee Cattermole's pub ban extended |newspaper=[[Daily Mirror]] |date=16 March 2011 |accessdate=16 October 2013}}</ref>\n\nFollowing a night out with teammates, Cattermole was arrested on 6 December 2011 along with then teammate [[Nicklas Bendtner]] and charged with damaging five cars on Stowell Street in Newcastle, close to St James' Park. On 25 March 2012, the case at Newcastle Magistrates Court was adjourned to be brought back before the same court on 16 April 2012. Charges against Bendtner were subsequently dropped.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.chroniclelive.co.uk/news/local-news/lee-cattermole-court-case-adjourned-1362294 |title=Lee Cattermole court case is adjourned in Newcastle |newspaper=[[Evening Chronicle]] |location=Newcastle upon Tyne |date=26 March 2012 |accessdate=16 October 2013}}</ref> Cattermole accepted a conditional caution and paid over \u00a34,000 in damages.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2012/apr/27/sunderland-captain-lee-cattermole-vandalising-cars | newspaper=The Guardian | location=London |title=Sunderland captain Lee Cattermole admits to vandalising cars | date=27 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n{{updated|match played 30 April 2019}}<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.soccerbase.com/players/player.sd?player_id=43076|title=Lee Cattermole|work=Soccerbase|publisher=Centurycomm|accessdate=6 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n{| class=wikitable style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Club\n!rowspan=2|Season\n!colspan=3|League\n!colspan=2|[[FA Cup]]\n!colspan=2|[[EFL Cup|League Cup]]\n!colspan=2|Other\n!colspan=2|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=4|[[Middlesbrough F.C.|Middlesbrough]]||[[2005\u201306 Middlesbrough F.C. season|2005\u201306]]\n|[[Premier League]]\n|14||1||5||0||0||0||5{{efn|name=UEFA|Appearances in [[UEFA Europa League|UEFA Cup]]}}||0||24||1\n|-\n|[[2006\u201307 Middlesbrough F.C. season|2006\u201307]]\n|Premier League\n|31||1||7||1||1||0||colspan=2|\u2014||39||2\n|-\n|[[2007\u201308 Middlesbrough F.C. season|2007\u201308]]\n|Premier League\n|24||1||2||0||2||0||colspan=2|\u2014||28||1\n|-\n!colspan=2|Total\n!69!!3!!14!!1!!3!!0!!5!!0!!91!!4\n|-\n|[[Wigan Athletic F.C.|Wigan Athletic]]||[[2008\u201309 Wigan Athletic F.C. season|2008\u201309]]\n|Premier League\n|33||1||0||0||2||1||colspan=2|\u2014||35||2\n|-\n|rowspan=11|[[Sunderland A.F.C.|Sunderland]]\n|[[2009\u201310 in English football|2009\u201310]]\n|Premier League\n|22||0||0||0||0||0||colspan=2|\u2014||22||0\n|-\n|[[2010\u201311 in English football|2010\u201311]]\n|Premier League\n|23||0||0||0||1||0||colspan=2|\u2014||24||0\n|-\n|[[2011\u201312 in English football|2011\u201312]]\n|Premier League\n|23||0||3||0||1||0||colspan=2|\u2014||27||0\n|-\n|[[2012\u201313 in English football|2012\u201313]]\n|Premier League\n|10||0||1||0||3||0||colspan=2|\u2014||14||0\n|-\n|[[2013\u201314 in English football|2013\u201314]]\n|Premier League\n|24||1||3||0||5||0||colspan=2|\u2014||32||1\n|-\n|[[2014\u201315 Sunderland A.F.C. season|2014\u201315]]\n|Premier League\n|28||1||0||0||0||0||colspan=2|\u2014||28||1\n|-\n|[[2015\u201316 Sunderland A.F.C. season|2015\u201316]]\n|Premier League\n|31||0||1||0||2||0||colspan=2|\u2014||34||0\n|-\n|[[2016\u201317 Sunderland A.F.C. season|2016\u201317]]\n|Premier League\n|8||0||0||0||1||0||colspan=2|\u2014||9||0\n|-\n|[[2017\u201318 Sunderland A.F.C. season|2017\u201318]]\n|[[EFL Championship|Championship]]\n|35||1||0||0||0||0||0||0||35||1\n|-\n|[[2018\u201319 Sunderland A.F.C. season|2018\u201319]]\n|[[EFL League One|League One]]\n|29||7||1||0||1||0||2{{efn|Appearances in [[EFL Trophy]]}}||0||33||7\n|-\n!colspan=2|Total\n!233!!10!!9!!0!!14!!0!!2!!0!!258!!10\n|-\n!colspan=3|Career total\n!335!!14!!23!!1!!19!!1!!7!!0!!384!!16\n|}\n\n{{notelist}}\n\n==Honours==\n'''Middlesbrough'''\n*[[UEFA Cup]] runner-up: [[2005\u201306 UEFA Cup|2005\u201306]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/4751467.stm |title=Middlesbrough 0\u20134 Sevilla |website=BBC Sport |date=10 May 2006 |accessdate=7 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n'''Sunderland'''\n*[[Football League Cup]] runner-up: [[2013\u201314 Football League Cup|2013\u201314]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/26311649 |title=Manchester City 3\u20131 Sunderland |first=Phil |last=McNulty |website=BBC Sport |date=2 March 2014 |accessdate=7 May 2019}}</ref>\n*[[EFL Trophy]] runner-up: [[2018\u201319 EFL Trophy|2018\u201319]]<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47709134 |title=Portsmouth 2\u20132 Sunderland |first=Adam |last=Williams |website=BBC Sport |date=31 March 2019 |accessdate=7 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n'''England U21'''\n*[[UEFA European Under-21 Championship]] runner-up: [[2009 UEFA European Under-21 Championship|2009]]<ref>{{cite new |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/internationals/8122457.stm |title=Germany U21 4\u20130 England U21 |first=David |last=McIntyre |website=BBC Sport |date=29 June 2009 |accessdate=7 May 2019}}</ref>\n\n'''Individual'''\n*North East Football Writers' Association's Player of the Year: 2014<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.sunderlandecho.com/sport/sunderland-afc/cattermole-beats-colback-to-be-named-player-of-year-by-football-writers-1-6947148 |title=Cattermole beats Colback to be named player of year by football writers |newspaper=[[Sunderland Echo]] |first=Chris |last=Young |date=11 November 2014 |accessdate=31 May 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150114203207/http://www.sunderlandecho.com/sport/sunderland-afc/cattermole-beats-colback-to-be-named-player-of-year-by-football-writers-1-6947148 |archive-date=14 January 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n*{{Soccerbase}}\n\n{{VVV-Venlo squad}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Cattermole, Lee}}\n[[Category:1988 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Stockton-on-Tees]]\n[[Category:Footballers from County Durham]]\n[[Category:English footballers]]\n[[Category:England youth international footballers]]\n[[Category:England under-21 international footballers]]\n[[Category:Association football midfielders]]\n[[Category:Middlesbrough F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Wigan Athletic F.C. players]]\n[[Category:Sunderland A.F.C. players]]\n[[Category:VVV-Venlo players]]\n[[Category:Premier League players]]\n[[Category:English Football League players]]\n", "name_user": "2a02:c7f:5658:2c00:10fe:a3e9:15dc:ef92", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lee_Cattermole"}
{"title_page": "Crystal City, Arlington, Virginia", "text_new": "{{More footnotes|date=July 2009}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name = Crystal City, Arlington, Virginia\n| settlement_type = [[Urban area]]\n| image_skyline = crystalcity.jpg\n| imagesize = 250px\n| image_caption = Downtown Crystal City in October 2005\n| image_map = Crystal City satellite image.jpg\n| mapsize = 250px\n| image_map1 = \n| mapsize1 = \n| map_caption = Satellite image of the interlocking highrises of Crystal City. [[Jefferson Davis Highway]] ([[U.S. Route 1 in Virginia|U.S. 1]]) can be seen running from north to south left of the image center. The main terminal of [[Ronald Reagan Washington National Airport|National Airport]] is in the bottom right corner of the image; the [[George Washington Memorial Parkway]] is to the left of the airport and right of the tree line. A few lanes of [[I-395 (VA)|I-395]] are visible in the top left corner, immediately beyond which is [[the Pentagon]]. At the bottom is [[State Route 233 (Virginia)|State Route 233]], the Airport Viaduct. Image from the [[United States Geological Survey]], taken April 26, 2002.\n| subdivision_type = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_type1 = [[U.S. state|State]]\n| subdivision_type2 = [[List of counties in Virginia|County]]\n| subdivision_name = {{nowrap|{{flagu|United States|name=United States of America|size=23px}}}}\n| subdivision_name1 = {{flag|Virginia|size=23px}}\n| subdivision_name2 = {{flagicon image|Flag of Arlington County, Virginia.svg|size=23px}} [[Arlington County, Virginia|Arlington]]\n| government_type = \n| established_date = Estimated at 1963\n| area_magnitude = \n| area_total_km2 = \n| area_land_km2 = \n| area_water_km2 = \n| population_as_of = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n| population_total = 22,543\n| population_metro = \n| population_urban = \n| population_density_km2 = \n| timezone = [[Eastern Standard Time Zone|EST]]\n| utc_offset = -5\n| timezone_DST = [[Eastern Daylight Time|EDT]]\n| utc_offset_DST = -4\n| postal_code_type = [[ZIP Code]]s\n| postal_code = 22202\n| area_code = [[Area code 703|703]]\n| elevation_ft = \n| coordinates = {{coord|38|51|5.05|N|77|3|2.48|W|region:US-VA|display=inline,title}}\n| area_total_sq_mi = \n| area_land_sq_mi = \n| area_water_sq_mi = \n| elevation_m = \n}}\n\n'''Crystal City''' is an urban neighborhood in the southeastern corner of [[Arlington County, Virginia]], south of downtown [[Washington, D.C.]] Due to its extensive integration of office buildings and residential high-rise buildings using underground corridors, travel between stores, offices, and residences is possible without going above ground; thus, a large part of Crystal City is an [[underground city]].\n\nCrystal City includes offices of numerous defense contractors, the [[United States Department of Labor]], the [[United States Marshals Service]] and many satellite offices for [[The Pentagon]]. It is also the location of [[Ronald Reagan Washington National Airport]].\n\n==Geography==\nCrystal City is centered along a stretch of Richmond Highway ([[U.S. Route 1 in Virginia|U.S. 1]]), just south of [[The Pentagon]], just east of [[Pentagon City]], and within walking distance to the west of [[Ronald Reagan Washington National Airport]]. Characterized as one of many \"urban villages\" by Arlington County, Crystal City is almost exclusively populated by high-rise apartment buildings, corporate offices, hotels, and numerous shops and restaurants. There is also an extensive network of underground shopping areas and connecting corridors beneath Crystal City.\n\nCrystal City has a [[Crystal City (Washington Metro)|station]] on the [[Washington Metro]] [[Blue Line (Washington Metro)|Blue]] and [[Yellow Line (Washington Metro)|Yellow Lines]], and [[Crystal City (VRE station)|another]] on the [[Virginia Railway Express]] [[commuter train]] system.\n\nThe layout of Crystal City was considered avant-garde at the time of construction, with [[city block|superblocks]] bounded by arterial and circulating roads, and with pedestrian traffic and the businesses serving it relocated from the streets to the pedestrian tunnels. However, Crystal City has since been redesigned to give it a more traditional, urban feel, with restaurants at street level, and with traffic patterns changed to make streets like Crystal Drive function as city streets, rather than as circulating roads.<ref name=\"ggw\">{{cite web|url=http://greatergreaterwashington.org/post.cgi?id=2565|title=Envisioning Crystal City as part of a larger community|publisher=Greater Greater Washington|date=2009-05-14|accessdate=2009-10-26|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100612222655/http://greatergreaterwashington.org/post.cgi?id=2565|archivedate=2010-06-12}}</ref>\n\nAs a consequence of Crystal City's extensive integration with both office buildings and residential high-rise buildings, it is possible for most residents living to the east of Route 1 to traverse from one end to the other (roughly north-south), performing shopping or dining along the way, entirely underground, thus making a large part of Crystal City an [[underground city]]. This is of particular convenience during inclement weather.\n\n== History ==\n[[Image:2345 Crystal Drive Hbrackett.jpg|left|thumb|alt=Brown metal and glass building, curved at the center and angled at the sides/|Crystal Park Four, former US Airways headquarters in July 2009.]]\nBefore development by the Charles E. Smith Company, the area was mostly composed of industrial sites, junkyards, and low-rent motels. A [[drive-in theater]] existed at the intersection of Jefferson Davis Highway and 20th Street South between 1947 and 1963 and is visible on aerial photos of the period. The [[Richmond, Fredericksburg & Potomac Railroad|RF&P]] railroad tracks were moved closer to National Airport to accommodate more space for development.\n\nThough it is not a [[planned community]], it unfolded in much that fashion after construction began on the first few condominiums and office buildings in 1963. The name \"Crystal City\" came from the first building, which was called ''Crystal House'' and had an elaborate crystal chandelier in the lobby. Every subsequent building took on the Crystal name (e.g., Crystal Gateway, Crystal Towers) and eventually the whole neighborhood. Crystal City is largely integrated in layout and extensive landscaping, as well as the style and materials of the high rise buildings, most of which have a speckled granite exterior.\n\nCrystal City's ''Crystal Underground'' shopping mall opened in September 1976. Billed as a \"turn-of-the-century shopping village,\" it featured antique leaded glass shop windows and cobblestone \"streets.\" Emphasis was on locally owned and operated businesses and personalized service. The largest retail outlets were a {{convert|12000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} [[Jelleff's]] women's store, Larimers gourmet grocery and delicatessen, and a [[Drug Fair]]. The mall also featured an \"Antique Alley\" with small antique and craft stores. At opening there were 40 stores, with an anticipated expansion of {{convert|150000|sqft|m2}} with 70 more shops including the Crystal Palace food court.<ref>\"Crystal Underground opens,\" by Pat Royse, ''The Washington Post'', Sep 30, 1976, p. VA_14.</ref>\n\nOn June 26, 2004, the Crystal City area underwent a number of changes. Many buildings' addresses were changed on this date, several major roads were turned into two-way streets, and many of the markings for the traditional building names (e.g., \"Crystal Gateway 1\") were removed. As a result, local residents may refer to building names that are difficult for visitors to find.<ref name=\"daw\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dwheeler.com/essays/crystal-city.html |title=Crystal City Name Changes (Address Changes) |author=David A. Wheeler |accessdate=2010-11-01}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Arlington County developed the [https://arlingtonva.s3.amazonaws.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2014/03/sprc_Jul3012_SectorPlan_CrystalCityPO.pdf Crystal City Sector Plan], which presented the community\u2019s vision to transform Crystal City into a more inviting, lively and walkable community with more ground floor retail, better quality office space and more housing options. This 40-year plan won the American Planning Association\u2019s 2013 National Planning Achievement Award for Innovation in Economic Planning and Development. It pioneers the use of economic analysis for planning purposes and is among the first of its kind to closely study the economics of demolishing and replacing major commercial buildings.\n\n<br />\n[[File:Crystal City Metro headhouse 2016.jpg|thumb|Crystal city metro station in 2016.]]\n\n==Economy==\nCrystal City currently has over 22,000 residents, while around 60,000 come to work there every weekday.<ref name=\"lw\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/local/counties/arlngton/longterm/wwlive/crystal.htm|title=Crystal City: Model of Convenience|author=Linda Wheeler|publisher=Washington Post|date=1995-03-25|accessdate=2009-10-26}}</ref> Once home to numerous Federal agencies, Crystal City\u2019s claim to fame now is not just its prime location next to Reagan National Airport, the Pentagon and dozens of Arlington\u2019s best eateries, but also as the place to be for thriving entrepreneurs. \n\nPlaces like [https://www.eastern-foundry.com/crystal-city-coworking Eastern Foundry] U.Group have made their homes in Crystal City specifically to target entrepreneurs \u2500 the people who are creating the innovation technologies that will become the way of the future. It is home to the [[United States Marshals Service]] and numerous Department of Defense offices. It also has offices of numerous defense contractors, the [[United States Environmental Protection Agency|Environmental Protection Agency]], the [[General Services Administration]], and many satellite offices for [[The Pentagon]], especially during the [[Pentagon Renovation Program]].<ref>{{cite news |author=E.L. Wasson |url=http://ny.therealdeal.com/articles/washington-dc-threatened-crystal-city-closures-appear-derailed-2 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081202192825/http://ny.therealdeal.com/articles/washington-dc-threatened-crystal-city-closures-appear-derailed-2 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2008-12-02 |title=Washington, D.C.: Threatened Crystal City closures appear derailed &#124; The Real Deal &#124; New York Real Estate News |publisher=Ny.therealdeal.com |date=2007-12-01 |accessdate=2009-07-16 }}</ref> Pentagon offices in Crystal City include the headquarters of the [[Army Wounded Warrior Program|Warrior Transition Command]] and the [[Special Inspector General for Afghanistan Reconstruction]].\n\nAt one time [[US Airways]] had its headquarters in Crystal Park Four in Crystal City.<ref>\"[http://airconsumer.dot.gov/rules/19950714.htm THE FOLLOWING LETTER WAS SENT TO THE ATTACHED LIST OF U.S. & FOREIGN AIRLINE, and TRAVEL AGENCY EXECUTIVES] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130218132328/http://airconsumer.dot.gov/rules/19950714.htm |date=2013-02-18 }}.\" ''[[U.S. Department of Transportation]]''. July 14, 1995. Retrieved on March 1, 2010.</ref> After US Airways merged with [[America West Airlines]] in 2005, the combined company closed the Virginia headquarters and moved the management to [[Tempe, Arizona]], in [[Greater Phoenix]].<ref>\"[http://www.accessmylibrary.com/article-1G1-134335017/us-airways-move-headquarters.html US Airways to move headquarters to Tempe, Ariz., early in 2006.]\" ''[[The Tribune (Arizona)|The Tribune]]''. July 23, 2005. Retrieved on March 1, 2010.</ref> Today, the Crystal City neighborhood is also home to headquarters for Lidl, Lyft, Bloomberg BNA and others.\n\nCrystal City is home to several associations and technology companies, including Muscular Dystrophy Association, [[American Diabetes Association]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/washington/breaking_ground/2015/01/american-diabetes-association-to-move-headquarters.html|title=American Diabetes Association to shift headquarters from Alexandria to Crystal City|author=Daniel J. Sernovitz|date=January 20, 2015|website=[[Washington Business Journal]]}}</ref> [[American Public Power Association]],  [[PBS]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvtechnology.com/news/the-pbs-no-downtime-move|title=The PBS No Downtime Move|author=|date=|publisher=|accessdate=8 November 2018}}</ref>, and [[Consumer Technology Association]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cta.tech/|title=CTA - home|website=CTA|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref> and more.\n\nOn November 13, 2018, [[Amazon (company)|Amazon.com]] announced that Arlington's Crystal City neighborhood would be the location of one of two campuses for its [[Amazon HQ2]], with the other campus planned for [[Long Island City]] in [[Queens]], New York City. Both campuses would have 25,000 workers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/amazon-in-advanced-talks-about-putting-hq2-in-northern-virginia-those-close-to-process-say/2018/11/02/9be831d6-d7c0-11e8-aeb7-ddcad4a0a54e_story.html|title=Amazon in advanced talks about putting HQ2 in Northern Virginia, those close to process say|last=O'Connell|first=Jonathan|last2=McCartney|first2=Robert|date=November 5, 2018|website=Washington Post}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|url=https://press.aboutamazon.com/news-releases/news-release-details/amazon-selects-new-york-city-and-northern-virginia-new|title=Amazon Selects New York City and Northern Virginia for New Headquarters|publisher=Amazon|date=November 13, 2018|accessdate=November 13, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last=Stevens | first=Laura | last2=Morris | first2=Keiko | last3=Honan | first3=Katie | title=Amazon Picks New York City, Northern Virginia for Its HQ2 Locations | website=Wall Street Journal | date=November 13, 2018 | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/amazon-chooses-new-york-city-and-northern-virginia-for-additional-headquarters-1542075336 | access-date=November 13, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=Amazon's Grand Search For 2nd Headquarters Ends With Split: NYC And D.C. Suburb | website=NPR.org | date=November 13, 2018 | url=https://www.npr.org/2018/11/13/665646050/amazons-grand-search-for-2nd-headquarters-ends-with-split-nyc-and-d-c-suburb | access-date=November 13, 2018}}</ref> In Amazon's announcement, a joint press release was presented by the Northern Virginia bidders that Amazon's HQ2 neighborhood location would be jointly marketed as \"[[National Landing]]\", which encompasses not only Crystal City but also [[Pentagon City]] and [[Potomac Yard]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/nation-now/2018/11/13/where-amazon-hq-2-national-landing-long-island-city/1987015002/|title=National Landing? Long Island City? This is where Amazon's headquarters are located|work=USA Today}}</ref> In February 2019, Amazon decided to cancel its plans for the Queens location for HQ2 and instead focus exclusively on the Crystal City/Pentagon City site. Construction is currently ongoing.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2005/06/05/AR2005060501108.html|title=Crystal City Attempts to Change for The Better|last=Silverman|first=Elissa|date=2005-06-06|work=The Washington Post|pages=D01|accessdate=2009-03-24}}\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/2016/04/20/realestate/commercial/crystal-city-once-cast-off-by-washington-reboots-itself.html www.nytimes.com/2016/04/20/realestate/commercial/crystal-city-once-cast-off-by-washington-reboots-itself.html]\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikivoyage|Arlington/Crystal City}}\n*[http://www.commuterpage.com/art/villages/crystalcity.htm Arlington's Urban Villages \u2013 Crystal City]\n*[http://www.dwheeler.com/essays/crystal-city.html Crystal City Name Changes (Address Changes)]\n\n{{Arlington County, Virginia}}\n\n[[Category:Crystal City, Arlington, Virginia| ]]\n[[Category:Neighborhoods in Arlington County, Virginia]]\n[[Category:Underground cities]]\n[[Category:Transit-oriented developments in the United States]]\n[[Category:Edge cities in the Baltimore-Washington metropolitan area]]\n", "text_old": "{{More footnotes|date=July 2009}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name = Crystal City, Arlington, Virginia\n| settlement_type = [[Urban area]]\n| image_skyline = crystalcity.jpg\n| imagesize = 250px\n| image_caption = Downtown Crystal City in October 2005\n| image_map = Crystal City satellite image.jpg\n| mapsize = 250px\n| image_map1 = \n| mapsize1 = \n| map_caption = Satellite image of the interlocking highrises of Crystal City. [[Jefferson Davis Highway]] ([[U.S. Route 1 in Virginia|U.S. 1]]) can be seen running from north to south left of the image center. The main terminal of [[Ronald Reagan Washington National Airport|National Airport]] is in the bottom right corner of the image; the [[George Washington Memorial Parkway]] is to the left of the airport and right of the tree line. A few lanes of [[I-395 (VA)|I-395]] are visible in the top left corner, immediately beyond which is [[the Pentagon]]. At the bottom is [[State Route 233 (Virginia)|State Route 233]], the Airport Viaduct. Image from the [[United States Geological Survey]], taken April 26, 2002.\n| subdivision_type = [[List of sovereign states|Country]]\n| subdivision_type1 = [[U.S. state|State]]\n| subdivision_type2 = [[List of counties in Virginia|County]]\n| subdivision_name = {{nowrap|{{flagu|United States|name=United States of America|size=23px}}}}\n| subdivision_name1 = {{flag|Virginia|size=23px}}\n| subdivision_name2 = {{flagicon image|Flag of Arlington County, Virginia.svg|size=23px}} [[Arlington County, Virginia|Arlington]]\n| government_type = \n| established_date = Estimated at 1963\n| area_magnitude = \n| area_total_km2 = \n| area_land_km2 = \n| area_water_km2 = \n| population_as_of = [[2010 United States Census|2010]]\n| population_total = 22,543\n| population_metro = \n| population_urban = \n| population_density_km2 = \n| timezone = [[Eastern Standard Time Zone|EST]]\n| utc_offset = -5\n| timezone_DST = [[Eastern Daylight Time|EDT]]\n| utc_offset_DST = -4\n| postal_code_type = [[ZIP Code]]s\n| postal_code = 22202\n| area_code = [[Area code 703|703]]\n| elevation_ft = \n| coordinates = {{coord|38|51|5.05|N|77|3|2.48|W|region:US-VA|display=inline,title}}\n| area_total_sq_mi = \n| area_land_sq_mi = \n| area_water_sq_mi = \n| elevation_m = \n}}\n\n'''Crystal City''' is an urban neighborhood in the southeastern corner of [[Arlington County, Virginia]], south of downtown [[Washington, D.C.]] Due to its extensive integration of office buildings and residential high-rise buildings using underground corridors, travel between stores, offices, and residences is possible without going above ground; thus, a large part of Crystal City is an [[underground city]].\n\nCrystal City includes offices of numerous defense contractors, the [[United States Department of Labor]], the [[United States Marshals Service]] and many satellite offices for [[The Pentagon]]. It is also the location of [[Ronald Reagan Washington National Airport]].\n\n==Geography==\nCrystal City is centered along a stretch of Richmond Highway ([[U.S. Route 1 in Virginia|U.S. 1]]), just south of [[The Pentagon]], just east of [[Pentagon City]], and within walking distance to the west of [[Ronald Reagan Washington National Airport]]. Characterized as one of many \"urban villages\" by Arlington County, Crystal City is almost exclusively populated by high-rise apartment buildings, corporate offices, hotels, and numerous shops and restaurants. There is also an extensive network of underground shopping areas and connecting corridors beneath Crystal City.\n\nCrystal City has a [[Crystal City (Washington Metro)|station]] on the [[Washington Metro]] [[Blue Line (Washington Metro)|Blue]] and [[Yellow Line (Washington Metro)|Yellow Lines]], and [[Crystal City (VRE station)|another]] on the [[Virginia Railway Express]] [[commuter train]] system.\n\nThe layout of Crystal City was considered avant-garde at the time of construction, with [[city block|superblocks]] bounded by arterial and circulating roads, and with pedestrian traffic and the businesses serving it relocated from the streets to the pedestrian tunnels. However, Crystal City has since been redesigned to give it a more traditional, urban feel, with restaurants at street level, and with traffic patterns changed to make streets like Crystal Drive function as city streets, rather than as circulating roads.<ref name=\"ggw\">{{cite web|url=http://greatergreaterwashington.org/post.cgi?id=2565|title=Envisioning Crystal City as part of a larger community|publisher=Greater Greater Washington|date=2009-05-14|accessdate=2009-10-26|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100612222655/http://greatergreaterwashington.org/post.cgi?id=2565|archivedate=2010-06-12}}</ref>\n\nAs a consequence of Crystal City's extensive integration with both office buildings and residential high-rise buildings, it is possible for most residents living to the east of Route 1 to traverse from one end to the other (roughly north-south), performing shopping or dining along the way, entirely underground, thus making a large part of Crystal City an [[underground city]]. This is of particular convenience during inclement weather.\n\n== History ==\n[[Image:2345 Crystal Drive Hbrackett.jpg|left|thumb|alt=Brown metal and glass building, curved at the center and angled at the sides/|Crystal Park Four, former US Airways headquarters in July 2009.]]\nBefore development by the Charles E. Smith Company, the area was mostly composed of industrial sites, junkyards, and low-rent motels. A [[drive-in theater]] existed at the intersection of Jefferson Davis Highway and 20th Street South between 1947 and 1963 and is visible on aerial photos of the period. The [[Richmond, Fredericksburg & Potomac Railroad|RF&P]] railroad tracks were moved closer to National Airport to accommodate more space for development.\n\nThough it is not a [[planned community]], it unfolded in much that fashion after construction began on the first few condominiums and office buildings in 1963. The name \"Crystal City\" came from the first building, which was called ''Crystal House'' and had an elaborate crystal chandelier in the lobby. Every subsequent building took on the Crystal name (e.g., Crystal Gateway, Crystal Towers) and eventually the whole neighborhood. Crystal City is largely integrated in layout and extensive landscaping, as well as the style and materials of the high rise buildings, most of which have a speckled granite exterior.\n\nCrystal City's ''Crystal Underground'' shopping mall opened in September 1976. Billed as a \"turn-of-the-century shopping village,\" it featured antique leaded glass shop windows and cobblestone \"streets.\" Emphasis was on locally owned and operated businesses and personalized service. The largest retail outlets were a {{convert|12000|sqft|m2|adj=on}} [[Jelleff's]] women's store, Larimers gourmet grocery and delicatessen, and a [[Drug Fair]]. The mall also featured an \"Antique Alley\" with small antique and craft stores. At opening there were 40 stores, with an anticipated expansion of {{convert|150000|sqft|m2}} with 70 more shops including the Crystal Palace food court.<ref>\"Crystal Underground opens,\" by Pat Royse, ''The Washington Post'', Sep 30, 1976, p. VA_14.</ref>\n\nOn June 26, 2004, the Crystal City area underwent a number of changes. Many buildings' addresses were changed on this date, several major roads were turned into two-way streets, and many of the markings for the traditional building names (e.g., \"Crystal Gateway 1\") were removed. As a result, local residents may refer to building names that are difficult for visitors to find.<ref name=\"daw\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dwheeler.com/essays/crystal-city.html |title=Crystal City Name Changes (Address Changes) |author=David A. Wheeler |accessdate=2010-11-01}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Arlington County developed the [https://arlingtonva.s3.amazonaws.com/wp-content/uploads/sites/5/2014/03/sprc_Jul3012_SectorPlan_CrystalCityPO.pdf Crystal City Sector Plan], which presented the community\u2019s vision to transform Crystal City into a more inviting, lively and walkable community with more ground floor retail, better quality office space and more housing options. This 40-year plan won the American Planning Association\u2019s 2013 National Planning Achievement Award for Innovation in Economic Planning and Development. It pioneers the use of economic analysis for planning purposes and is among the first of its kind to closely study the economics of demolishing and replacing major commercial buildings.\n\n<br />\n[[File:Crystal City Metro headhouse 2016.jpg|thumb|Crystal city metro station in 2016.]]\n\n==Economy==\nCrystal City currently has over 22,000 residents, while around 60,000 come to work there every weekday.<ref name=\"lw\">{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-srv/local/counties/arlngton/longterm/wwlive/crystal.htm|title=Crystal City: Model of Convenience|author=Linda Wheeler|publisher=Washington Post|date=1995-03-25|accessdate=2009-10-26}}</ref> Once home to numerous Federal agencies, Crystal City\u2019s claim to fame now is not just its prime location next to Reagan National Airport, the Pentagon and dozens of Arlington\u2019s best eateries, but also as the place to be for thriving entrepreneurs. \n\nPlaces like [https://www.eastern-foundry.com/crystal-city-coworking Eastern Foundry] U.Group have made their homes in Crystal City specifically to target entrepreneurs \u2500 the people who are creating the innovation technologies that will become the way of the future. It is home to the [[United States Marshals Service]] and numerous Department of Defense offices. It also has offices of numerous defense contractors, the [[United States Environmental Protection Agency|Environmental Protection Agency]], the [[General Services Administration]], and many satellite offices for [[The Pentagon]], especially during the [[Pentagon Renovation Program]].<ref>{{cite news |author=E.L. Wasson |url=http://ny.therealdeal.com/articles/washington-dc-threatened-crystal-city-closures-appear-derailed-2 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081202192825/http://ny.therealdeal.com/articles/washington-dc-threatened-crystal-city-closures-appear-derailed-2 |url-status=dead |archive-date=2008-12-02 |title=Washington, D.C.: Threatened Crystal City closures appear derailed &#124; The Real Deal &#124; New York Real Estate News |publisher=Ny.therealdeal.com |date=2007-12-01 |accessdate=2009-07-16 }}</ref> Pentagon offices in Crystal City include the headquarters of the [[Army Wounded Warrior Program|Warrior Transition Command]] and the [[Special Inspector General for Afghanistan Reconstruction]].\n\nAt one time [[US Airways]] had its headquarters in Crystal Park Four in Crystal City.<ref>\"[http://airconsumer.dot.gov/rules/19950714.htm THE FOLLOWING LETTER WAS SENT TO THE ATTACHED LIST OF U.S. & FOREIGN AIRLINE, and TRAVEL AGENCY EXECUTIVES] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130218132328/http://airconsumer.dot.gov/rules/19950714.htm |date=2013-02-18 }}.\" ''[[U.S. Department of Transportation]]''. July 14, 1995. Retrieved on March 1, 2010.</ref> After US Airways merged with [[America West Airlines]] in 2005, the combined company closed the Virginia headquarters and moved the management to [[Tempe, Arizona]], in [[Greater Phoenix]].<ref>\"[http://www.accessmylibrary.com/article-1G1-134335017/us-airways-move-headquarters.html US Airways to move headquarters to Tempe, Ariz., early in 2006.]\" ''[[The Tribune (Arizona)|The Tribune]]''. July 23, 2005. Retrieved on March 1, 2010.</ref> Today, the Crystal City neighborhood is also home to headquarters for Lidl, Lyft, Bloomberg BNA and others.\n\nCrystal City is home to several associations and technology companies, including Muscular Dystrophy Association, [[American Diabetes Association]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/washington/breaking_ground/2015/01/american-diabetes-association-to-move-headquarters.html|title=American Diabetes Association to shift headquarters from Alexandria to Crystal City|author=Daniel J. Sernovitz|date=January 20, 2015|website=[[Washington Business Journal]]}}</ref> [[American Public Power Association]],  [[PBS]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tvtechnology.com/news/the-pbs-no-downtime-move|title=The PBS No Downtime Move|author=|date=|publisher=|accessdate=8 November 2018}}</ref>, and [[Consumer Technology Association]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cta.tech/|title=CTA - home|website=CTA|access-date=2019-03-04}}</ref> and more.\n\nOn November 13, 2018, [[Amazon (company)|Amazon.com]] announced that Arlington's Crystal City neighborhood would be the location of one of two campuses for its [[Amazon HQ2]], with the other campus planned for [[Long Island City]] in [[Queens]], New York City. Both campuses would have 25,000 workers.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/local/amazon-in-advanced-talks-about-putting-hq2-in-northern-virginia-those-close-to-process-say/2018/11/02/9be831d6-d7c0-11e8-aeb7-ddcad4a0a54e_story.html|title=Amazon in advanced talks about putting HQ2 in Northern Virginia, those close to process say|last=O'Connell|first=Jonathan|last2=McCartney|first2=Robert|date=November 5, 2018|website=Washington Post}}</ref> <ref>{{cite web|url=https://press.aboutamazon.com/news-releases/news-release-details/amazon-selects-new-york-city-and-northern-virginia-new|title=Amazon Selects New York City and Northern Virginia for New Headquarters|publisher=Amazon|date=November 13, 2018|accessdate=November 13, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | last=Stevens | first=Laura | last2=Morris | first2=Keiko | last3=Honan | first3=Katie | title=Amazon Picks New York City, Northern Virginia for Its HQ2 Locations | website=Wall Street Journal | date=November 13, 2018 | url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/amazon-chooses-new-york-city-and-northern-virginia-for-additional-headquarters-1542075336 | access-date=November 13, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | title=Amazon's Grand Search For 2nd Headquarters Ends With Split: NYC And D.C. Suburb | website=NPR.org | date=November 13, 2018 | url=https://www.npr.org/2018/11/13/665646050/amazons-grand-search-for-2nd-headquarters-ends-with-split-nyc-and-d-c-suburb | access-date=November 13, 2018}}</ref> In Amazon's announcement, a joint press release was presented by the Northern Virginia bidders that Amazon's HQ2 neighborhood location would be jointly marketed as \"[[National Landing]]\", which encompasses not only Crystal City but also [[Pentagon City]] and [[Potomac Yard]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/tech/nation-now/2018/11/13/where-amazon-hq-2-national-landing-long-island-city/1987015002/|title=National Landing? Long Island City? This is where Amazon's headquarters are located|work=USA Today}}</ref> In February 2019, Amazon decided to cancel its plans for the Queens location for HQ2 and instead focus exclusively on the Crystal City/Pentagon City site. \n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/wp-dyn/content/article/2005/06/05/AR2005060501108.html|title=Crystal City Attempts to Change for The Better|last=Silverman|first=Elissa|date=2005-06-06|work=The Washington Post|pages=D01|accessdate=2009-03-24}}\n* [https://www.nytimes.com/2016/04/20/realestate/commercial/crystal-city-once-cast-off-by-washington-reboots-itself.html www.nytimes.com/2016/04/20/realestate/commercial/crystal-city-once-cast-off-by-washington-reboots-itself.html]\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikivoyage|Arlington/Crystal City}}\n*[http://www.commuterpage.com/art/villages/crystalcity.htm Arlington's Urban Villages \u2013 Crystal City]\n*[http://www.dwheeler.com/essays/crystal-city.html Crystal City Name Changes (Address Changes)]\